text: Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 31A (DEE31A), also known exactly as DEE31 and Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 31, is categorized under autosomal dominant diseases and is a specific type of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE31A is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests in the first months or years of life with refractory seizures and global developmental delay from early infancy, caused by a heterozygous mutation in the DNM1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 5 (DEE5), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 5, is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically falling under the category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by global developmental delay and the onset in the first months of life of tonic seizures or infantile spasms. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically through a heterozygous mutation in the SPTAN1 gene on chromosome 9q34.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 14 (DEE14), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 14, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. It is characterized by a specific type of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. More precisely, DEE14 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by refractory focal seizures that begin by 6 months of age and an arrest of psychomotor development. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the KCNT1 gene located on chromosome 9q34.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 3 (DEE3) is a type of autosomal recessive disease and belongs to the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE3 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests in the first months of life with erratic, typically myoclonic, refractory seizures. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC25A22 gene located on chromosome 11p15. Additionally, Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 3 is also known by its exact synonym, Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 3.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 49 (DEE49), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 49, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a specific condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. DEE49 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by the neonatal onset of seizures, global developmental delay with intellectual disability and lack of speech, hypotonia, spasticity, and coarse facial features. This condition is attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DENND5A gene located on chromosome 11p15.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 41 (DEE41), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 41, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by the onset of seizures, severely impaired psychomotor development, and brain anomalies, including delayed myelination, thin corpus callosum, and cerebral atrophy within the first days or weeks of life. These symptoms have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SLC1A2 gene located on chromosome 11p13. This condition is also an example of a disorder that, by definition, has some autosomal dominant inheritance aspect.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 21 (DEE21), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 21, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE21 is distinguished by its onset in the first months of life, marked by intractable seizures and severely impaired psychomotor development, which is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the NECAP1 gene located on chromosome 12p13.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 27 (DEE27), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 27, is a specific type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by being a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE27 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by early onset seizures, delayed psychomotor development, and intellectual disability of variable severity, which is due to a heterozygous mutation in the GRIN2B gene located on chromosome 12p12.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 13 (DEE13), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 13, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy. It is characterized by a form of ailment that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE13 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by the commencement of intractable seizures within the first year of life, coupled with impaired development or developmental regression following the onset of seizures. This condition is attributed to a heterozygous mutation in the SCN8A gene located on chromosome 12q13.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 66 (DEE66), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 66, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. More specifically, DEE66 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy with onset in the first days or weeks of life, featuring seizures, global developmental delay accompanied by hypotonia, behavioral abnormalities, and either dysmorphic features or ophthalmologic defects. This condition is directly linked to a heterozygous mutation in the PACS2 gene located on chromosome 14q32.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 43 (DEE43), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 43, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by the onset in the first year of life of seizures, global developmental delay, and mild to moderate intellectual disability. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the GABRB3 gene on chromosome 15q11.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 48 (DEE48), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 48, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. It is a condition that arises from autosomal recessive inheritance, which involves the material basis of the disease. DEE48 is specifically characterized by seizures that begin before the age of 1 year, global developmental delay, intellectual disability, absent speech, and minimal or absent motor development. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AP3B2 gene on chromosome 15q25.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 16 (DEE16), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 16, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a type of condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. DEE16 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy where seizures begin in the first weeks or months of life, accompanied by delayed or regression of psychomotor development, and hypotonia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TBC1D24 gene located on chromosome 16p13.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 17 (DEE17), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 17, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This specific encephalopathy is characterized by the onset in the first weeks or months of life of intractable seizures and very poor psychomotor development. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GNAO1 gene located on chromosome 16q13, demonstrating that it is a condition with at least some basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 29 (DEE29), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 29, is an autosomal recessive disease and a type of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. DEE29 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy with onset in the first months of life, featuring refractory myoclonic seizures, poor overall growth, congenital microcephaly with cerebral atrophy, impaired myelination as seen on brain imaging, spasticity with abnormal movements, peripheral neuropathy, and poor visual fixation. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the AARS1 gene on chromosome 16q22.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 28 (DEE28), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 28, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests in the first months of life with refractory seizures, severe axial hypotonia, and profoundly impaired psychomotor development, resulting from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the WWOX gene on chromosome 16q23.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 25 (DEE25), also known as developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 25, with amelogenesis imperfecta and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 25, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a variant of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a specific set of features, including onset in early infancy of refractory seizures, global developmental delay with intellectual disability, persistent neurological symptoms, and dental anomalies. The condition primarily arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC13A5 gene on chromosome 17p13. Moreover, DEE25 is defined by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with intellectual disability as a key feature.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 42 (DEE42), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 42, is a type of Autosomal Dominant Disease and falls under the category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by the onset of seizures in the first hours or days of life and a global developmental delay with severely impaired intellectual development. The underlying cause of DEE42 is a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1A gene located on chromosome 19p13, which is an example of a condition that has a material basis in Autosomal Dominant Inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 52 (DEE52), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 52, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is a condition that arises due to material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE52 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the infantile onset of refractory seizures and global neurological development delay, along with intellectual disability. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCN1B gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 46 (DEE46), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 46, is a type of Autosomal Dominant Disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. It is characterized by a specific condition that emerges from a material basis in Autosomal Dominant Inheritance. This encephalopathy is defined by the onset in the first months or years of life of intractable seizures, global developmental delay, failure to thrive, hypotonia, hyperreflexia, and variably impaired intellectual development. The condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GRIN2D gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Microcephaly seizures and developmental delay is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and is also recognized as a form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is associated with a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically characterized as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests with microcephaly, the infantile onset of seizures, and developmental delay. This condition arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PNKP gene located on chromosome 19q13. Furthermore, microcephaly seizures and developmental delay is precisely known as developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 10 and is also referred to as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 10.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 35 (DEE35), also known as ITPA-related encephalopathy or early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 35, is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is marked by the onset of seizures in the first months of life, the absence of normal development, and the absence of myelination of early neurological structures. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ITPA gene located on chromosome 20p13.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 12 (DEE12), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 12, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition originates from a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset of refractory seizures within the first year of life. Initially, affected individuals may exhibit normal to mild developmental delays before the onset of seizures; however, post-seizure onset, they experience developmental regression and stagnation. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PLCB1 gene located on chromosome 20p12.3.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 34 (DEE34), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 34, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by an infantile onset of refractory migrating focal seizures, developmental regression, and severe global impairment. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC12A5 gene located on chromosome 20q12, indicating that it arises from some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 26 (DEE26), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 26, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE26 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the onset in the first years of life of seizures, developmental delay, intellectual disability, poor speech, and behavioral abnormalities. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KCNB1 gene on chromosome 20q13.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 7 (DEE7) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE7 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by the infantile onset of refractory seizures, delayed neurological development, and persistent neurologic abnormalities, caused by a heterozygous mutation in the KCNQ2 gene on chromosome 20q13. Additionally, DEE7 is known by several exact synonyms, including KCNQ2-related epileptic encephalopathy, KCNQ2-related neonatal epileptic encephalopathy, and Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 7.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 33 (DEE33), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 33, is a type of autosomal dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by its material basis in at least some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE33 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that begins in the first months of life, featuring seizures and severe global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development, along with poor or absent speech. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the EEF1A2 gene located on chromosome 20q13.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 53 (DEE53), also known as early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 53, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy. This condition is characterized by a type of disorder that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, DEE53 is defined by the infantile onset of intractable seizures, hypotonia, poor or absent global development, severe intellectual disability, and spastic quadriplegia. This is due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SYNJ1 gene located on chromosome 21q22.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 30 (DEE30), also known precisely as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 30, is classified as a type of Autosomal Dominant Disease and falls within the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is specifically characterized by an onset in the first few months of life of refractory seizures and severely impaired or absent developmental progress. It stems from a heterozygous mutation in the SIK1 gene on chromosome 21q22, indicating that it has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 2 (DEE2), also known exactly as EIEE2, X-linked infantile spasm syndrome 2, and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 2, is a type of X-linked dominant disease that falls under the broader category of developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a type of condition that invariably has a material basis in some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE2 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy marked by the X-linked dominant inheritance of seizure onset in the first months of life, along with intellectual disability and poor motor control. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the CDKL5 gene located on chromosome Xp22.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 1 (DEE1), also known precisely as X-linked Infantile Spasm Syndrome 1 and Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 1, is a type of X-linked recessive disease. It falls under the broader category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy and is characterized by a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. DEE1 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by frequent tonic seizures or spasms beginning in infancy due to a mutation in the ARX gene on chromosome Xp21.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 36 (DEE36) is recognized as a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy, as well as a type of X-linked dominant disease. It is characterized by its basis in a certain type of inheritance, specifically something that at least has a material basis in X-linked dominant inheritance. The detailed definition of DEE36 outlines it as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by an X-linked dominant inheritance pattern. This condition typically manifests with infantile onset of seizures, delayed psychomotor development, and in some cases, dysmorphic features. These symptoms have a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ALG13 gene located on chromosome Xq23. Additionally, DEE36 is also known by its exact synonyms, including congenital disorder of glycosylation, type Is, and early infantile epileptic encephalopathy 36.

Developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 92 (DEE92) is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is categorized under developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by a condition that arises due to at least some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, DEE92 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests with seizures beginning in infancy or early childhood, alongside global developmental delay and varying degrees of intellectual disability. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GABRB2 gene located on chromosome 5q34.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 91 (DEE91) is a type of autosomal dominant disease, specifically classified under developmental and epileptic encephalopathies. It is characterized by its nature of having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. DEE91 is defined as a developmental and epileptic encephalopathy that manifests through the onset of refractory multifocal seizures within the first weeks or years of life, accompanied by delayed psychomotor development, poor or absent speech, and severe to profound intellectual disability. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PPP3CA gene located on chromosome 4q24. Additionally, DEE91 is also known by its exact synonym, Infantile or Early Childhood Epileptic Encephalopathy 1.

Developmental delay and seizures with or without movement abnormalities is a type of syndromic intellectual disability and also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a phenotype characterized by some neurodevelopmental delay. It is defined as a syndromic intellectual disability characterized by global developmental delay, variable intellectual disability, and early-onset seizures with a myoclonic component. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the DHDDS gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Pustular psoriasis 14 is identified as a specific type of psoriasis characterized by sudden, repeated episodes of high-grade fever, generalized rash, and disseminated pustules, accompanied by hyperleukocytosis and elevated serum levels of C-reactive protein. This condition arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IL36RN gene located on chromosome 2q14. Additionally, pustular psoriasis 14 is exactly synonymous with acrodermatitis continua of Hallopeau and deficiency of IL-36R antagonist.
Psoriasis 2 is a type of psoriasis, which is characterized by a psoriasis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CARD14 gene located on chromosome 17q25.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1A is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX1 gene on chromosome 7q21. It also has the exact synonym "peroxisome biogenesis disorder 1A (Zellweger)."

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 2A is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and has an exact synonym: peroxisome biogenesis disorder 2A (Zellweger). It is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX5 gene on chromosome 12p13.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 3a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and has the exact synonym peroxisome biogenesis disorder 3A (Zellweger). It is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX12 gene on chromosome 17.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 4a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and has an exact synonym, peroxisome biogenesis disorder 4A (Zellweger). It is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX6 gene on chromosome 6p21.1.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 5A is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and it is defined by a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX2 gene on chromosome 8q21. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with peroxisome biogenesis disorder 5A (Zellweger).

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 6a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and has the exact synonym peroxisome biogenesis disorder 6A (Zellweger). It is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX10 gene on chromosome 1p36.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 7a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and has an exact synonym, peroxisome biogenesis disorder 7A (Zellweger). It is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX26 gene on chromosome 22q11.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 8a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX16 gene on chromosome 11p11. Additionally, peroxisome biogenesis disorder 8a is exactly synonymous with peroxisome biogenesis disorder 8A (Zellweger).

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 10a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PEX3 gene located on chromosome 6q24. Additionally, peroxisome biogenesis disorder 10a is exactly synonymous with peroxisome biogenesis disorder 10A (Zellweger).

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 11a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX13 gene on chromosome 2p15. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "peroxisome biogenesis disorder 11A (Zellweger)."

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 12a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, which is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PEX19 gene on chromosome 1q23. It is exactly synonymous with peroxisome biogenesis disorder 12A (Zellweger).

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 13a is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and has a definition as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the PEX14 gene on chromosome 1p36. It also has an exact synonym, peroxisome biogenesis disorder 13A (Zellweger).
Mucolipidosis is a type of lipid storage disease, characterized by increased storage of carbohydrates and lipids.

GM1 gangliosidosis type 3 is a form of GM1 gangliosidosis and is also classified as a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a GM1 gangliosidosis variant which is marked by neurodegeneration and mild skeletal changes, with the age at onset spanning from 3 to 30 years. Additionally, it is precisely referred to as adult-onset GM1 gangliosidosis.
Mucolipidosis Type IV is a type of mucolipidosis that is defined by delayed development and vision impairment that worsens over time.

Cerebral cavernous malformation 1 is a type of cerebral cavernous malformation, defined as a cerebral cavernous malformation that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRIT1 gene on chromosome 7q21.

Leukocyte adhesion deficiency 2 is a type of leukocyte adhesion deficiency that is defined by the absence of Sialyl Lewis X of E-selectin. This condition results in recurrent bacterial infections, severe growth delay, and severe intellectual deficit.

Ovarian dysgenesis 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that arises due to a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the follicle-stimulating hormone receptor located on chromosome 2p16.

Ovarian dysgenesis 2 is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, and it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that has its material basis in a mutation in the BMP15 gene on chromosome Xp11.

Ovarian dysgenesis 3 is classified as an autosomal recessive disease and a type of 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, ovarian dysgenesis 3 is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that originates from a homozygous mutation in the PSMC3IP gene located on chromosome 17q12-q21.

Ovarian dysgenesis 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MCM9 gene on chromosome 6q22.

Ovarian dysgenesis 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SOHLH1 gene on chromosome 9q34.

Ovarian dysgenesis 6 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also classified as a type of 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis and involves a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that results from a homozygous mutation in the NUP107 gene located on chromosome 12q15.

Ovarian dysgenesis 7 is classified as an autosomal recessive disease and is a specific type of 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, ovarian dysgenesis 7 is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that results from a homozygous mutation in the MRPS22 gene located on chromosome 3q23.

Ovarian dysgenesis 8 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it is also a type of 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis, which indicates that it falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, ovarian dysgenesis 8 is defined as a 46 XX gonadal dysgenesis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ESR2 gene located on chromosome 14q23.

GM1 gangliosidosis type 2 is a type of GM1 gangliosidosis, which is characterized by slowly progressive generalized neurodegeneration and mild skeletal changes, with onset between 7 months and 3 years of age. It is also precisely known as juvenile GM1 gangliosidosis.

GM1 gangliosidosis type 1 is a type of GM1 gangliosidosis and also falls under the category of conditions that have, at the very least, the symptom of hepatosplenomegaly. It is defined as a GM1 gangliosidosis characterized by rapid psychomotor deterioration beginning within 6 months of birth, involving widespread central nervous system implications, hepatosplenomegaly, facial dysmorphism, macular cherry-red spots, skeletal dysplasia, and results in early death.

Multiple congenital anomalies hypotonia seizures syndrome is a type of physical disorder, a type of lipid metabolism disorder, and a type of condition that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a lipid metabolism disorder characterized by severe global developmental delay, hypotonia, and early-onset seizures, associated with multiple cardiac, genitourinary, and gastrointestinal congenital anomalies.

Parkinson's disease 22 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also a type of late-onset Parkinson's disease. It is categorized as something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, Parkinson's disease 22 is defined as a late onset Parkinson's disease that has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a heterozygous mutation in the coiled-coil-helix-coiled-coil-helix domain containing 2 gene on chromosome 7p11.2. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: autosomal dominant Parkinson's disease 22.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of Cornelia de Lange Syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal dominant inheritance. Moreover, Cornelia de Lange Syndrome 1 is defined by a Cornelia de Lange syndrome that originates from a heterozygous mutation in the NIPBL gene, encoding a component of the cohesin complex, located on chromosome 5p13.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome 2 is a type of Cornelia de Lange Syndrome and falls under the category of X-linked dominant diseases. It also represents a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of X-linked dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by a mutation in the SMC1A gene, which encodes a subunit of the cohesin complex, located on chromosome Xp11.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome 3 (CdLS3) is a type of Cornelia de Lange Syndrome, which is an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of CdLS3 is a Cornelia de Lange syndrome that results from a heterozygous mutation in the SMC3 gene located on chromosome 10q25.2. CdLS3 is exactly synonymous with CDLS3 and also known as Cornelia De Lange Syndrome 3 with or without midline brain defects.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome 4 (CDLS4), also known exactly as Cornelia De Lange Syndrome 4 with or without midline brain defects, is a specific type of Cornelia de Lange Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by a Cornelia de Lange syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the RAD21 gene, which is a part of the cohesin complex, located on chromosome 8q24. This condition is an example of a disorder that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Cornelia de Lange Syndrome 5 is a type of Cornelia de Lange Syndrome and an X-linked dominant disease. It is defined as a Cornelia de Lange Syndrome that has a material basis in a mutation in the HDAC8 gene on chromosome Xq13. This implies it is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex localized type is a form of autosomal dominant disease and a subtype of epidermolysis bullosa simplex. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific type of epidermolysis bullosa simplex is defined by skin blistering that can start anytime between childhood and adulthood, typically confined to the hands and feet. Additionally, it is precisely synonymous with epidermolysis bullosa simplex Weber-Cockayne type.

Epidermolysis bullosa simplex generalized type is a type of autosomal dominant disease and is also known as epidermolysis bullosa simplex Koebner type. It falls under the category of epidermolysis bullosa simplex and is a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined by widespread blisters that appear at birth or in early infancy.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 1 is a type of Meier-Gorlin syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as a Meier-Gorlin syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ORC1 gene located on chromosome 1p32.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 2 is a subtype of Meier-Gorlin syndrome, which is characterized as an autosomal recessive disease. This particular syndrome not only falls under the category of diseases with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance but is also specifically defined by having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ORC4 gene located on chromosome 2q23.

Meier Gorlin syndrome 3 is a type of Meier Gorlin syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as a Meier-Gorlin syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ORC6 gene located on chromosome 16q11.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 4 is a type of Meier-Gorlin syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as a Meier-Gorlin syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDT1 gene located on chromosome 16q24.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 5 is a type of Meier-Gorlin syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined as a Meier-Gorlin syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the CDC6 gene located on chromosome 17q21.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 6 is a type of Meier-Gorlin syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined specifically as a Meier-Gorlin syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GMNN gene on chromosome 6p22.

Meier-Gorlin syndrome 7 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of Meier-Gorlin syndrome, characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Meier-Gorlin syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CDC45 gene on chromosome 22q11.

Papa syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by pyoderma gangrenosum, pyogenic arthritis, acne, and suppurative hidradenitis, with a heterozygous mutation in the PSTPIP1 gene on chromosome 15q24. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym "pyogenic arthritis, pyoderma gangrenosum, and acne."

TN polyagglutination syndrome is a type of hematopoietic system disease. It is defined as a hematopoietic system disease characterized by red blood cells that agglutinate upon exposure to almost all human sera, but not to autologous serum or the sera of newborns. This condition has a material basis in somatic mutations in the C1GALT1C1 gene located on chromosome Xq24. TN polyagglutination syndrome is also exactly synonymous with galactosyltransferase deficiency.

Lung non-squamous non-small cell carcinoma is a type of lung non-small cell carcinoma, which is characterized by the absence of evidence of squamous differentiation. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, "non-squamous NSCLC."
Anaplastic carcinoma is a type of thyroid gland carcinoma that is defined by being composed of undifferentiated cells. It is also exactly synonymous with anaplastic thyroid carcinoma.

Adult onset leukoencephalopathy with axonal spheroids and pigmented glia is a type of autosomal dominant disease, a type of leukodystrophy, and a condition that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and whose existence starts during adult onset. It is characterized by progressive dementia, apraxia, apathy, impaired balance, parkinsonism, spasticity, and epilepsy, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the CSF1R gene on chromosome 5q32. This condition is also exactly synonymous with hereditary diffuse leukoencephalopathy with spheroids.

Thyroid gland adenocarcinoma is a type of adenocarcinoma and also a type of thyroid gland carcinoma. It falls under the category of conditions that at least derive from an entity that intersects with epithelial cells and entities that have an origin in some gland. Additionally, thyroid gland adenocarcinoma is defined as a thyroid gland carcinoma that derives from epithelial cells of glandular origin.
Differentiated thyroid gland carcinoma is a type of thyroid gland adenocarcinoma, which is characterized by extensive evidence of follicular cell differentiation.

Bronchiectasis 1 is a type of bronchiectasis and an autosomal dominant disease, which is a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a bronchiectasis that has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding the beta subunit of the epithelial sodium channel on chromosome 16p12.

Bronchiectasis 2 is a type of bronchiectasis that is characterized as an autosomal dominant disease. It falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, bronchiectasis 2 is defined as a form of bronchiectasis that has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding the alpha subunit of the epithelial sodium channel.

Bronchiectasis 3 is a type of bronchiectasis and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a bronchiectasis that has a material basis in mutation in the gene encoding the gamma subunit of the epithelial sodium channel.

Granular Corneal Dystrophy 1 is a specific type of Granular Corneal Dystrophy, which is also known by its exact synonym, Corneal Dystrophy, Groenouw Type I. This condition is characterized by recurrent erosions and gray crumb-like opacification located in the cornea, along with proteinaceous rock candy-like deposits in the anterior stroma and subepithelium. It leads to progressive vision loss later in life as the deposits move into the central vision. The material basis for Granular Corneal Dystrophy 1 lies in autosomal dominant inheritance, particularly due to a heterozygous mutation of the transforming growth factor beta-induced gene located on chromosome 5q31.1, which encodes keratoepithelin. This genetic abnormality leads to increased protein deposition and disruption of the corneal surface.

Dedifferentiated liposarcoma is a type of liposarcoma that is defined as a high-grade tumor characterized by the transformation of a lower-grade tumor into a new high-grade tumor through the creation of new high-grade cells.

Smarca4 deficient sarcoma of thorax is a type of thoracic cancer, which has an exact synonym SMARCA4-DTS. It is defined as a thoracic cancer characterized by poorly differentiated neoplasms with epithelioid/rhabdoid cells organized in a solid pattern, and its material basis lies in alterations in the switch/sucrose nonfermenting complex, also known in humans as BRG1-associated factors (BAF chromatin remodeling complex).

Carney Stratakis syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a syndrome that has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by the presence of multicentric paragangliomas and multifocal gastrointestinal stromal sarcoma tumors.

Myxofibrosarcoma is a type of sarcoma that is defined as a sarcoma arising from the soft tissue, characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped cells, cellular pleomorphism, thin-walled blood vessels, fibrous septa, and myxoid stroma. Additionally, myxofibrosarcoma has an exact synonym, fibromyxoid sarcoma.

Hypermanganesemia with dystonia is a type of metal metabolism disorder, characterized by involuntary, sustained muscle contractions (dystonia) and other uncontrolled movements resulting from excessive accumulation of manganese.

Hypermanganesemia with dystonia 1 is a specific type of hypermanganesemia with dystonia, which is characterized by increased serum manganese, motor neurodegeneration with extrapyramidal features, polycythemia, and hepatic dysfunction. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the SLC30A10 gene located on chromosome 1q41. Additionally, hypermanganesemia with dystonia 1 is classified as a condition that includes at least some hepatic dysfunction as a symptom.

Hypermanganesemia with dystonia 2 is a type of hypermanganesemia with dystonia, which is defined as a hypermanganesemia with dystonia predominantly characterized by the loss of motor milestones in the first years of life. It has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SLC39A14 gene located on chromosome 8p21.

Sweeney Cox Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that notably involves a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by distinctive facial dysostosis, which includes hypertelorism, deficiencies of the eyelids and facial bones, cleft palate/velopharyngeal insufficiency, and low-set cupped ears. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TWIST1 gene located on chromosome 7p21.
Peho syndrome is a type of brain disease characterized by extreme cerebellar atrophy due to almost total granule neuron loss.

Galactosialidosis is a type of lysosomal storage disease characterized by a combined deficiency of beta-galactosidase and neuraminidase. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CTSA gene located on chromosome 20q13.
Hyperprolinemia is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder, defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the excess of proline in the blood.

Hyperprolinemia type 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of hyperprolinemia, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hyperprolinemia that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the proline dehydrogenase gene located on chromosome 22q11. Additionally, hyperprolinemia type 1 is exactly synonymous with hyperprolinemia type I.

Hyperprolinemia type 2, also known exactly as hyperprolinemia type II, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of hyperprolinemia. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically defined as a hyperprolinemia that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Hyper IgM syndrome is a type of hyperimmunoglobulin syndrome characterized by an immune system that fails to produce normal levels of the antibodies IgA, IgG, and IgE but can produce normal or elevated levels of IgM. It is also known by its exact synonyms: HIGM, hyperimmunoglobulin M syndrome, and immunodeficiency with hyper-IgM. Furthermore, Hyper IgM syndrome is precisely matched with several medical coding and classification systems, including ICD10CM:D80.5, MESH:D053306, NCI:C3990, OMIM:PS308230, and UMLS_CUI:C0272236.

Hyper IgE syndrome is a type of hyperimmunoglobulin syndrome that is defined as a hyperimmunoglobulin syndrome characterized by eczema, distinct facial features, a tendency to experience bone fractures, and recurrent bacterial infections of the skin and lungs. It also has the exact synonym hyper immunoglobulin E syndrome.

Non-alcoholic fatty liver is a type of metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease characterized by the absence of inflammation and hepatocyte injury in the form of hepatocyte ballooning. It has the exact synonyms NAFL and nonalcoholic fatty liver.

Metabolic Dysfunction Associated Steatohepatitis (MASH), also known as Non-Alcoholic Steatohepatitis (NASH) or Nonalcoholic Steatohepatitis, is a type of Metabolic Dysfunction Associated Steatotic Liver Disease. It is characterized by a metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease that includes inflammation with hepatocyte injury such as ballooning, with or without fibrosis. This condition is a subtype of something that at least has liver inflammation as a symptom.

Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines 1 is a type of Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines, which is defined as a Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PTPN11 gene on chromosome 12q24. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with LEOPARD syndrome 1.

Noonan Syndrome with Multiple Lentigines 2 is a type of Noonan Syndrome with Multiple Lentigines, which is defined as a Noonan Syndrome with multiple lentigines that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the RAF1 gene on chromosome 3p25. Additionally, Noonan Syndrome with Multiple Lentigines 2 is exactly synonymous with LEOPARD Syndrome 2.

Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines 3 is a type of Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines, which is defined as a Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BRAF gene located on chromosome 7q34. Additionally, Noonan syndrome with multiple lentigines 3 is exactly synonymous with LEOPARD syndrome 3.

Naxos disease is a type of nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma, which is defined as a nonepidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma characterized by palmoplantar keratoderma, woolly hair, and arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the plakoglobin gene on chromosome 17q21.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IA (CDG-IA) is a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CDG-IA is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I that is marked by severe encephalopathy with axial hypotonia, abnormal eye movement, pronounced psychomotor retardation, peripheral neuropathy, cerebellar hypoplasia, and retinitis pigmentosa. The disorder has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding phosphomannomutase-2 on chromosome 16p13. Additionally, CDG-IA is exactly synonymous with PMM2-Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation and Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1A.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IAA, also exactly known as congenital disorder of glycosylation 1AA, is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally has an autosomal recessive inheritance and is also based on abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The disorder is specifically defined by fibroblasts with reduced dolichol profiles and enhanced accumulation of free cholesterol, caused by a homozygous mutation in the NUS1 gene on chromosome 6q22.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IB (CDG-Ib) is a subtype of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a range of symptoms including bleeding and vomiting, and it has a disease basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CDG-Ib is specifically defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by features such as protein-losing enteropathy, cyclic vomiting, profound hypoglycemia, failure to thrive, liver fibrosis, hypoalbuminemia, life-threatening intestinal bleeding of diffuse origin, protein C and S deficiency, low anti-thrombin III levels. Its molecular basis is linked to compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding mannose phosphate isomerase on chromosome 15q24. Furthermore, CDG-Ib is exactly synonymous with Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1b.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IC (CDG-IC) is a subtype of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and is also categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is linked to abnormalities in prenatal development or birth. Specifically, CDG-IC is defined by psychomotor retardation with delayed walking and speech, hypotonia, seizures, and sometimes protein-losing enteropathy. This condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ALG6 gene located on chromosome 1p31. Additionally, Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IC is exactly synonymous with Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1C.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation Id is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I, as well as a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is also a condition that has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has a disease basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. This disorder is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I that is characterized by severe neurologic involvement associated with dysmorphism and visual impairment, and it has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ALG3 gene on chromosome 3q27. Furthermore, congenital disorder of glycosylation Id has an exact synonym, congenital disorder of glycosylation 1d.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IE (CDG-IE) is a subtype of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I, as well as a form of autosomal recessive disease. It is classified under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and diseases with origins in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CDG-IE is specifically defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by psychomotor delay, seizures, hypotonia, facial dysmorphism, and microcephaly, which results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPM1 gene located on chromosome 20q13. Additionally, CDG-IE is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1e.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation If, also known exactly as congenital disorder of glycosylation 1f, is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I. It falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, implying that its material basis is in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is linked to abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by psychomotor delay, seizures, failure to thrive, and cutaneous and ocular anomalies, with its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the MPDU1 gene on chromosome 17p13.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Ig (CDG-Ig) is a specific type within the Congenital Disorders of Glycosylation Type I category and is also classified as an autosomal recessive disease. This classification indicates that it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance, which is a type of inheritance pattern that at least has its disease basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CDG-Ig is characterized by facial dysmorphism (including a prominent forehead, large ears, and a thin upper lip), generalized hypotonia, feeding difficulties, moderate to severe developmental delay, progressive microcephaly, and frequent upper respiratory tract infections due to impaired immunity with decreased immunoglobulin levels, and decreased coagulation factors. The disorder is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding dolichyl-P-mannose:Man-7-GlcNAc-2-PP-dolichyl-alpha-6-mannosyltransferase located on chromosome 22q13. Furthermore, CDG-Ig is precisely synonymous with ALG12-Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation and Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1g.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IH (CDG-IH) is a subtype of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and an autosomal recessive disease, which means it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This condition is characterized by several symptoms, including ataxia, seizures, hepatomegaly, failure to thrive, left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity, ascites, edema, diarrhea, vomiting, feeding problems, and it also has a basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Moreover, CDG-IH is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I with a wide range of manifestations such as gastrointestinal symptoms (diarrhea, vomiting, feeding problems with failure to thrive, protein-losing enteropathy), edema and ascites (including hydrops fetalis), hepatomegaly, renal tubulopathy, coagulation anomalies due to thrombocytopenia, brain involvement (psychomotor delay, seizures, ataxia), facial dysmorphism (low-set ears and retrognathia), pes equinovarus, and muscular hypotonia. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding dolichyl-P-glucose:Glc-1-Man-9-GlcNAc-2-PP-dolichyl-alpha-3-glucosyltransferase on chromosome 11q14. CDG-IH is also known by its exact synonym, Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1H.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation II is a subtype of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital disorder of glycosylation II is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I that is distinguished by symptoms such as iris coloboma, cataract, infantile spasms, developmental delay, and abnormal coagulation factors, due to compound heterozygous mutation in the ALG2 gene on chromosome 9q22. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1i.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IJ (CDG-IJ) is a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and is also classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance and has its disease basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CDG-IJ is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by symptoms including hypotonia, intractable seizures, developmental delay, microcephaly, and severe fetal hypokinesia. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPAGT1 gene, which is responsible for encoding UDP-GlcNAc:dolichyl-phosphate N-acetylglucosamine phosphotransferase, located on chromosome 11q23. Furthermore, CDG-IJ has an exact synonym: Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1j.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IK is a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and is also classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is linked to autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. This disorder, also known exactly as Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1K, is defined as a Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation I characterized by severe developmental and psychomotor delay, muscular hypotonia, intractable early-onset seizures, and microcephaly. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding beta-1,4-mannosyltransferase on chromosome 16p13.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IL is a subtype of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This disorder is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and manifests symptoms such as left upper quadrant abdominal rigidity. It also has its disease foundation in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IL is specifically defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I that is distinguished by progressive microcephaly, hypotonia, developmental delay, drug-resistant infantile epilepsy, and hepatomegaly, all resulting from a homozygous mutation in the ALG9 gene on chromosome 11q23. Additionally, it is precisely synonymous with Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1L.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IM (CDG-IM) is a subtype of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and is also classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined by a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and involves some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. CDG-IM is characterized by muscular hypotonia and ichthyosis, with its material basis being a homozygous mutation in the DOLK gene. This gene encodes the enzyme responsible for the final step of the de novo biosynthesis of dolichol phosphate, located on chromosome 9q34. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation IM is exactly synonymous with DOLK-congenital disorder of glycosylation, congenital disorder of glycosylation 1m, and dolichol kinase deficiency.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation I is a subtype of several categories: it is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I, a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it falls under categories that have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and diseases that have a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is specifically defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by symptoms such as poorly coordinated suck resulting in difficulty feeding and failure to thrive, myoclonic jerks with hypotonia and brisk reflexes progressing to a seizure disorder, roving eyes, developmental delay, poor to absent visual contact, and sensorineural hearing loss. This disorder has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RFT1 gene on chromosome 3p21. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation I is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1n.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IP is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and causes symptoms such as bleeding and vomiting. Furthermore, this condition can be based on abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. A specific definition of congenital disorder of glycosylation IP outlines it as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by facial dysmorphism (including microcephaly, high forehead, low posterior hairline, strabismus), hypotonia, failure to thrive, intractable seizures, developmental delay, persistent vomiting, and gastric bleeding. This disorder is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ALG11 gene on chromosome 13q14. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation IP is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1p.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IQ is a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a highly variable phenotype typically presenting with severe visual impairment, variable ocular anomalies such as optic nerve hypoplasia/atrophy, iris and optic nerve coloboma, congenital cataract, glaucoma, intellectual disability, cerebellar abnormalities, nystagmus, hypotonia, ataxia, and/or ichthyosiform skin lesions. This disorder at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is related to phenotypes like visual impairment, optic nerve hypoplasia, iris coloboma, nystagmus, ataxia, hypotonia, cerebellar atrophy, aplasia hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis, and congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma. Additionally, it has a basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The congenital disorder of glycosylation IQ has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SRD5A3 gene on chromosome 4q12 and has the exact synonym congenital disorder of glycosylation 1q.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IR is classified as a type of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I, and it also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This disorder is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with symptoms such as hepatic dysfunction. Furthermore, it has a basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IR is defined as a Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation I that is marked by failure to thrive, developmental delay, hypotonia, strabismus, and hepatic dysfunction, which is due to compound heterozygous mutation in the DDOST gene on chromosome 1p36. Additionally, Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IR is exactly synonymous with Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1R.

The congenital disorder of glycosylation is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and also falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and presents symptoms such as muscle weakness. Additionally, this disorder can have its basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. The congenital disorder of glycosylation is specifically identified as congenital disorder of glycosylation I, which displays a wide range of clinical manifestations. These commonly include a bifid uvula with or without cleft palate at birth, associated with growth delay, hepatopathy with elevated aminotransferase serum levels, myopathy that encompasses exercise-related fatigue, exercise intolerance, and muscle weakness, intermittent hypoglycemia, and potentially dilated cardiomyopathy and/or cardiac arrest. This is due to decreased phosphoglucomutase 1 enzyme activity and is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PGM1 gene on chromosome 1p31. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1t.

Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation IU, also known precisely as Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation 1U, is a specific subtype of Congenital Disorder of Glycosylation Type I and falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is noted for having its disease basis in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined by symptoms such as respiratory distress, severe hypotonia at birth, significant global developmental delays, early-onset intractable seizures, and myopathic fascies with craniofacial dysmorphisms like trigonocephaly/progressive microcephaly, low anterior hairline, arched eyebrows, hypotelorism, strabismus, a small nose, prominent philtrum, thin upper lip, high-arched palate, micrognathia, malocclusion, severe congenital flexion joint contractures, and elevated serum creatine kinase levels. The material basis for this disorder is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DPM2 gene on chromosome 9q34.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation Iw (CDG-Iw) is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CDG-Iw is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I characterized by developmental delay, intellectual disability, failure to thrive, hypotonia, and seizures. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the STT3A gene on chromosome 11q24. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation Iw is exactly synonymized with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1w.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation IX is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and is also classified as an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Specifically, congenital disorder of glycosylation IX is defined as a congenital disorder of glycosylation I that is characterized by intrauterine growth retardation, microcephaly, failure to thrive, developmental delay, intellectual disability, hypotonia, seizures, optic nerve atrophy, and respiratory difficulties. This condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the STT3B gene on chromosome 3p23. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation IX is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1x.

Congenital disorder of glycosylation Iy (CDG-Iy) is a type of congenital disorder of glycosylation type I and is also classified as a type of X-linked recessive disease. It is associated with X-linked recessive inheritance, which manifests through various symptoms including vomiting and has a foundation in abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. CDG-Iy is characterized by neurologic abnormalities such as global developmental delays in language, social skills, and motor development, intellectual disability, hypotonia, microcephaly, and seizures/epilepsy. Facial dysmorphism features include deep-set eyes, large ears, a hypoplastic vermillion of the upper lip, and a large mouth with widely spaced teeth. Patients may also experience feeding problems often due to chewing difficulties and aversion to food with certain textures, failure to thrive, gastrointestinal abnormalities like reflux or vomiting, and strabismus. The disorder stems from a hemizygous mutation in the SSR4 gene on chromosome Xq28. Additionally, congenital disorder of glycosylation Iy is exactly synonymous with congenital disorder of glycosylation 1y.

Larsen-like syndrome B3GAT3 type is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome, which also falls under the category of conditions with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by joint laxity, dislocations, and contractures, short stature, foot deformities such as clubfeet, broad fingertips and toes, a short neck, dysmorphic facial features including hypertelorism, downslanting palpebral fissures, an upturned nose with anteverted nares, a high arched palate, and various cardiac malformations. This condition is caused by a homozygous mutation in the B3GAT3 gene located on chromosome 11q12. Furthermore, Larsen-like syndrome B3GAT3 type is synonymously known as Larsen-like syndrome, B3GAT3 type, and multiple joint dislocations-short stature-craniofacial dysmorphism-congenital heart defects syndrome.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Genevieve type is a specific kind of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, which falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. This condition is characterized by infantile-onset severe developmental delay and skeletal dysplasia, which includes symptoms such as short stature, premature carpal ossification, platyspondyly, longitudinal metaphyseal striations, and small epiphyses. The genetic basis for this condition is related to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NANS gene located on chromosome 9q22. Furthermore, it is described as a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Polygenic disease, which is a type of genetic disease, is characterized by the additive contributions of variants in multiple genes at different loci. This is defined as a genetic disease that intersects with diseases that at least have a material basis in some form of polygenic inheritance.

A digenic disease is characterized as a type of polygenic disease that manifests through the expression of a phenotype, which necessitates the presence of pathogenic variants in two distinct genes. It is defined as a condition that intersects with diseases having at least a material basis in digenic inheritance. This implies that for a disease to be considered digenic, it must involve pathological variations in two separate genes, positioning it within the broader category of polygenic diseases.

3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase 1 deficiency is a type of 3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency. It is defined as a 3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the alpha subunit of 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase on chromosome 3q27.

3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase 2 deficiency is a type of 3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency. It is defined as a 3-Methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase deficiency that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the beta subunit of 3-methylcrotonyl-CoA carboxylase on chromosome 5q13.

Hyperekplexia 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, specifically a form of hyperekplexia that is characterized by extreme hypertonia, a stiff and rigid appearance, and has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ATAD1 gene on chromosome 10q23. Moreover, it is a condition that has at least a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, Hyperekplexia 4 has an exact match with OMIM:618011.

Hypotrichosis 14 is a specific type of hypotrichosis. It is defined by the presence of sparse to absent lanugo-like scalp hair, sparse and brittle eyebrows, sparse eyelashes, and sparse body hair. The material basis for hypotrichosis 14 is found in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LSS gene located on chromosome 21q22.

Wolfram Syndrome Mitochondrial Form is a type of Wolfram Syndrome and is also a type of condition that has a material basis in mitochondrial inheritance. This form of Wolfram Syndrome is defined by having a material basis in mutation in mtDNA. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms including DIDMOAD, mitochondrial form, and diabetes mellitus AND insipidus with optic atrophy AND deafness mitochondrial form.

Autosomal dominant Wolfram syndrome is a type of Wolfram syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by congenital progressive hearing impairment, diabetes mellitus, and optic atrophy. This condition is associated with a heterozygous mutation in the WFS1 gene on chromosome 4p16 and has its material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Van Maldergem Syndrome 1 is a type of Van Maldergem Syndrome and is defined as a Van Maldergem syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the DCHS1 gene located on chromosome 11p15.

Van Maldergem Syndrome 2 is a type of Van Maldergem Syndrome and is defined as a Van Maldergem Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FAT4 gene on chromosome 4q28.

Congenital myasthenic syndrome 22 is a type of congenital myasthenic syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a congenital myasthenic syndrome characterized by neonatal hypotonia, neonatal feeding problems, and nasal dysarthria, which arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PREPL gene on chromosome 2p21.

Agammaglobulinemia 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of agammaglobulinemia, which is characterized by having at least a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an agammaglobulinemia that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the LRRC8A gene on chromosome 9q34.

Klippel Feil Syndrome 1 is a type of Klippel Feil Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Klippel-Feil syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDF6 gene on chromosome 8q22.

Klippel Feil Syndrome 2 is a type of Klippel Feil Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a Klippel-Feil Syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the MEOX1 gene on chromosome 17q21.

Klippel Feil Syndrome 3 is a type of Klippel Feil Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a Klippel-Feil Syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDF3 gene on chromosome 12p13. This syndrome is also a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.

Klippel Feil Syndrome 4 is a type of Klippel Feil Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally relies on some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by having a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MYO18B gene located on chromosome 22q12.

Orofacial cleft 6 is a type of orofacial cleft and a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an orofacial cleft that has its material basis in variation in an enhancer of the IRF6 gene located on chromosome 1q32.

Hyper IgE recurrent infection syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of Hyper IgE syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, it is defined as a Hyper IgE syndrome that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DOCK8 gene located on chromosome 9p24.

Hyper IgE recurrent infection syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it is a subtype of hyper IgE syndrome. It is characterized as something that fundamentally stems from autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, the syndrome has a definition as a hyper IgE syndrome that is caused by a homozygous mutation in the ZNF341 gene located on chromosome 20q11.

Hyper IgE recurrent infection syndrome 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of Hyper IgE syndrome, which inherently involves a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Hyper IgE syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the IL6ST gene located on chromosome 5q11.
Kleefstra syndrome is a type of syndrome defined by developmental delay and intellectual disability, severely limited or absent speech, and weak muscle tone.

Kleefstra syndrome 2 is a type of Kleefstra syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.
