It is defined as a Kleefstra syndrome characterized by delayed psychomotor development, variable intellectual disability, and mild dysmorphic features, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KMT2C gene on chromosome 7q36.
Coronavirus infectious disease is a type of viral infectious disease and is defined as a viral infectious disease that has a material basis in Coronavirus.

COVID-19 is a type of coronavirus infectious disease that is transmitted through droplet spread transmission and airborne transmission. It is characterized by symptoms such as fever, cough, and dyspnea (shortness of breath). The disease is defined as a Coronavirus infectious disease characterized by fever, cough, and shortness of breath, and it has a material basis in SARS-CoV-2. COVID-19 is also known by several exact synonyms including 2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV), 2019-nCoV infection, COVID19, SARS-CoV-2 infection, Wuhan coronavirus infection, and Wuhan seafood market pneumonia virus infection.
A germ cell benign neoplasm is a type of cell type benign neoplasm, which is defined as a benign neoplasm that derives from germ cells.

A benign teratoma is identical to an entity that is both a benign neoplasm and intersects with an entity that is derived from at least some ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm. Further, a benign teratoma is classified as a type of germ cell benign neoplasm. Additionally, it is defined as a germ cell benign neoplasm that originates from mature tissue elements or a limited amount of immature tissue elements.
Ankylosing spondylitis 1 is a type of ankylosing spondylitis, defined as an ankylosing spondylitis that has a material basis in variation in the HLA-B27 allele on chromosome 6p21.3.

Ankylosing spondylitis 2 is a type of ankylosing spondylitis and is categorized as an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined by a specific form of ankylosing spondylitis that has a material basis in variation in the HLA-B27 allele located on chromosome 9q31-q34. This type of ankylosing spondylitis is also characterized as a condition that necessarily has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.
Ankylosing spondylitis 3 is a type of ankylosing spondylitis which is defined as an ankylosing spondylitis that has a material basis in variation in the HLA-B allele on chromosome 2q36.1-q36.3.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, and it is also a type of anterior segment dysgenesis. This condition is characterized by having at least a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, anterior segment dysgenesis 1 is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PITX3 gene located on chromosome 10q24.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 2 is a type of anterior segment dysgenesis and an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that has a material basis in homozygous, compound heterozygous, or heterozygous mutation in the FOXE3 gene on chromosome 1p33. This condition is also characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of anterior segment dysgenesis, characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the FOXC1 gene on chromosome 6p25.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of anterior segment dysgenesis, indicating it is something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that has its material basis in heterozygous mutation in the PITX2 gene on chromosome 4q25.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 5 is a type of anterior segment dysgenesis, defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PAX6 gene located on chromosome 11p13.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 6 is a type of anterior segment dysgenesis and is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the CYP1B1 gene on chromosome 2p22.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 7 is a type of anterior segment dysgenesis and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically involves a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PXDN gene on chromosome 2p25.

Anterior segment dysgenesis 8 is a type of anterior segment dysgenesis and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an anterior segment dysgenesis that results from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CPAMD8 gene located on chromosome 19p13.

Oculocutaneous albinism type VI is a type of oculocutaneous albinism. It is defined as an oculocutaneous albinism that has a material basis in an autosomal recessive null mutation of the SLC24A5 gene on chromosome 15q21.1.

Nephroma is defined as a benign neoplasm located in the kidney cortex, which is an intersection of benign neoplasms and diseases that have their location in both the cortex and the kidney. It is a type of kidney cortex disease and also a type of kidney benign neoplasm. Additionally, nephroma is precisely referred to as a benign nephroma.

Kidney cortex disease is equivalent to a condition that is both a disease and intersects with conditions that are diseases located in the cortex and diseases located in the kidney. Furthermore, kidney cortex disease is classified as a type of kidney disease. It is defined as a kidney disease that is located in the kidney cortex.

Lymph node benign neoplasm is defined as an immune system organ benign neoplasm that is located in the lymph nodes. It is the same as something that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease located in at least some lymph nodes. Additionally, it is a type of immune system organ benign neoplasm and also a type of lymph node disease.

Lymph node carcinoma is a type of lymph node cancer and a type of carcinoma, which is something that at least derives from some epithelial cell. It is defined as a lymph node cancer that has a material basis in abnormally proliferating cells which derive from epithelial cells.

Auditory system benign neoplasm is the same as something that is an intersection of a benign neoplasm and something that is at least a disease located in the auditory system. It is a type of sensory organ benign neoplasm and also a type of auditory system disease. Additionally, an auditory system benign neoplasm is defined as a sensory system benign neoplasm that is located in the auditory system.
Familial glucocorticoid deficiency is a type of adrenal gland disease and it is defined as an adrenal cortex disease characterized by insufficient production of glucocorticoids.

Glucocorticoid Deficiency 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and familial glucocorticoid deficiency. It is characterized by a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a familial glucocorticoid deficiency that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding the melanocortin-2 receptor, also known as the adrenocorticotropin receptor, located on chromosome 18p11.

Peroxisome biogenesis disorder 2b is a type of peroxisomal biogenesis disorder and an autosomal recessive disease, which essentially means it is a condition that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is specifically defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the PEX5 gene on chromosome 12p13.3.

Heimler syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a peroxisomal biogenesis disorder characterized by sensorineural hearing loss, generalized enamel hypoplasia of the permanent dentition with normal primary dentition, and nail defects. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PEX1 gene on chromosome 7q21. Furthermore, Heimler syndrome 1 has a broad synonym, Deafness-enamel hypoplasia-nail defects syndrome, and an exact synonym, peroxisomal biogenesis disorder 1C.

Heimler Syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, peroxisomal biogenesis disorder, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by sensorineural hearing loss, generalized enamel hypoplasia of the permanent dentition with normal primary dentition, and nail defects. This condition is due to compound heterozygous mutation in the PEX6 gene on chromosome 6p21. Furthermore, Heimler Syndrome 2 has an exact synonym, peroxisomal biogenesis disorder 4C.

Severe congenital neutropenia 1 is identified as a type of severe congenital neutropenia and an autosomal dominant disease, which essentially has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is also characterized by conditions that have their basis in some abnormalities of prenatal development or birth. Furthermore, it is defined specifically as a severe congenital neutropenia that results from a heterozygous mutation in the neutrophil elastase gene located on chromosome 19p13.

Corticosterone methyloxidase deficiency 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and adrenal gland disease, which also has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an adrenal gland disease that is characterized by excessive amounts of sodium released in the urine, along with insufficient release of potassium in the urine, usually beginning in the first few weeks of life. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, aldosterone synthase deficiency.

Alopecia mental retardation syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by the loss of hair on the scalp, eyebrows, eyelashes, axillas, and pubic hair, in addition to mild to severe intellectual disability.

Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 1 is a type of alopecia mental retardation syndrome and a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is also a type of condition that has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 1 is defined as an alopecia-mental retardation syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the AHSG gene located on chromosome 3q27.

Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of alopecia mental retardation syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by an alopecia-mental retardation syndrome that has its material basis in variation in chromosome 3q26.2-q26.31.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma is a type of B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia characterized by the presence of too many B-cell lymphoblasts in the blood and bone marrow. It has exact synonyms including B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma, B-ALL, and precursor B lymphoblastic lymphoma/leukemia.

Elsahy-Waters syndrome is a type of syndrome which is also known exactly as branchioskeletogenital syndrome. This syndrome is characterized by a variety of symptoms including brachycephaly, facial asymmetry, marked hypertelorism, proptosis, blepharochalasis, midface hypoplasia, a broad nose with a concave nasal ridge, and prognathism. Additionally, it features radicular dentin dysplasia leading to obliterated pulp chambers, apical translucent cysts, recurrent infections, and early loss of teeth; vertebral fusions, particularly at C2-C3; and moderate mental retardation. Among its symptoms, it at least has ptosis.

Fazio Londe disease is a type of autosomal recessive disease and progressive bulbar palsy, which is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by motor, sensory, and cranial neuronopathy and has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the C20ORF54 gene on chromosome 20p13. Additionally, Fazio Londe disease has an exact synonym: riboflavin transporter deficiency neuronopathy.
A developmental cardiac valvular defect is a type of physical disorder defined by a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLD1 gene on chromosome 3q26.

Nanophthalmos is a type of microphthalmia and is defined as a microphthalmia that is characterized by a small eye with a short axial length, severe hyperopia, an elevated lens/eye ratio, and a high incidence of angle-closure glaucoma.

Optic disc anomalies with retinal and/or macular dystrophy represent a condition that is classified as an autosomal recessive disease, a type of microphthalmia, and a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, this particular form of microphthalmia is defined by having its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the SIX6 gene located on chromosome 14q23.
Syndromic microphthalmia is a type of microphthalmia defined as a form of microphthalmia that occurs as part of a syndrome, affecting other organs and tissues in the body.
Isolated microphthalmia, which is a type of microphthalmia, is defined as a microphthalmia that occurs by itself.

B cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia is a type of lymphoma, a type of acute lymphoblastic leukemia, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some lymphocyte of B lineage. It is characterized by too many B-cell lymphoblasts (immature white blood cells) in the bone marrow and blood. Additionally, it has exact synonyms including B acute lymphoblastic leukemia and B-cell acute lymphocytic leukemia.
Bone sarcoma, a type of bone cancer, is defined as a bone cancer whose material basis is in abnormally proliferating cells derived from embryonic mesoderm.

A gallbladder benign neoplasm is the same as an entity that intersects with being both a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in the gallbladder. It is a type of biliary tract benign neoplasm and also classified as a type of gallbladder disease. Furthermore, a gallbladder benign neoplasm is defined as a biliary tract benign neoplasm that is located in the gallbladder.

Tongue carcinoma is a type of carcinoma and also a type of tongue cancer, which is something that at least derives from epithelial cells. It is defined as a tongue cancer that derives from epithelial cells covering the surface of the tongue.

Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) is a type of coronavirus infectious disease, which is also a type of condition that at least has symptoms including cough. MERS is defined as a coronavirus infectious disease characterized by severe respiratory illness, including fever, cough, and shortness of breath, and it has a material basis in MERS-CoV.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with BCR-ABL1 is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma that derives from B-lymphoblasts and carries a translocation between the BCR gene on chromosome 22 and the ABL1 gene on chromosome 9, resulting in the production of the p190 kd or p210 kd fusion protein. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms: B-ALL with BCR-ABL1 and B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with t(9;22)(q34.1;q11.2);BCR-ABL1.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma MLL rearranged is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma characterized by the presence of lymphoblasts that carry a translocation between the KMT2A gene at 11q23.3 and another gene partner, resulting in the production of a KMT2A related fusion protein. This condition is also exactly synonymous with B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with t(v;11q23); MLL rearranged, B-ALL KMT2A rearranged, B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma KMT2A rearranged, and B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with t(v;11q23.3); KMT2A rearranged.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with ETV6 RUNX1 is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma characterized by the presence of lymphoblasts that carry a translocation between the TEL gene on chromosome 12 and the AML1 gene on chromosome 21, (p13.2;q22.1), resulting in the production of the TEL-AML1 (ETV6-RUNX1) fusion protein. This condition also has exact synonyms, including B-ALL with ETV6-RUNX1 and B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with t(12;21)(p13.2;q22.1); ETV6-RUNX1.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with hyperdiploidy is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma that is composed of B-lymphoblasts which contain more than 50 and usually less than 66 chromosomes. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym: B-ALL with hyperdiploidy.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with hypodiploidy is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma that is composed of B-lymphoblasts which contain less than 46 chromosomes. Moreover, it has the exact synonym B-ALL with hypodiploidy.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with IL3 IGH represents a form of B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma characterized by the presence of lymphoblasts that exhibit a translocation between the IL3 gene on chromosome 5 and the IGH locus on chromosome 14, specifically at (q31.1;q32.3). Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with B-ALL with IL3-IGH and B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with t(5;14)(q31.1;q32.3) IL3-IGH.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with TCF3 PBX1 is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma characterized by the presence of lymphoblasts that carry a translocation between the E2A gene on chromosome 19 and the PBX1 gene on chromosome 1. This condition has several exact synonyms, including B Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia with t(1;19)(q23;p13.3); E2A-PBX1 (TCF3-PBX1), B-ALL with TCF3-PBX1, and B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with t(1;19)(q23;p13.3);TCF3-PBX1.

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma BCR-ABL1-like is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma that has a gene expression profile similar to that of B-ALL with t(9;22)(q34.1;q11.2) BCR-ABL1 but lacks that gene fusion. Additionally, it has exact synonyms including "B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma, BCR-ABL1-like" and "B-ALL BCR-ABL1like."

B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma with iAMP21 is a type of B lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma. It is defined as a B-lymphoblastic leukemia/lymphoma characterized by the amplification of a portion of chromosome 21. Additionally, this condition has exact synonyms, which include B-ALL with iAMP21 and Intrachromosomal amplification of chromosome 21 (iAMP21).

Calcium oxalate nephrolithiasis is a type of nephrolithiasis that is defined as a nephrolithiasis characterized by stones composed of calcium oxalate. This condition has a material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the SLC26A1 gene on chromosome 4p16.
Urolithiasis is a type of urinary system disease, which is defined as a urinary system disease characterized by the formation of stony concretions in the bladder or urinary tract.
Uric acid urolithiasis is a type of urolithiasis that is defined by the composition of the stones being predominantly urate.
Hypophosphatemic nephrolithiasis osteoporosis is a type of kidney disease characterized by the formation of renal calcium stones or bone demineralization.

45 x 46 XY mixed gonadal dysgenesis is a type of mixed gonadal dysgenesis. It is defined as a mixed gonadal dysgenesis characterized by asymmetrical gonadal development in an individual with a mosaic karyotype of 45,X/46,XY.

Nonsyndromic aplasia cutis congenita is a type of skin disease, which is defined as a skin disease characterized by localized areas of missing skin that resemble ulcers or open wounds in newborns. This condition has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BMS1 gene on chromosome 10q11.

Atrial standstill 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of heart conduction disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a heart conduction disease characterized by a transient or permanent absence of electrical and mechanical atrial activity, which has its material basis in the coinheritance of a variant in the SCN5A gene in combination with a rare connexin-40 genotype.

Atrial standstill 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of heart conduction disease, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a heart conduction disease characterized by a transient or permanent absence of electrical and mechanical atrial activity, with its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the NPPA gene on chromosome 1p36.

Diaphyseal medullary stenosis with malignant fibrous histiocytoma, also known exactly as Hardcastle syndrome, bone dysplasia-medullary fibrosarcoma syndrome, and diaphyseal medullary stenosis-malignant fibrous histiocytoma syndrome, is a type of osteochondrodysplasia and an autosomal dominant disease. This condition is characterized as an osteochondrodysplasia that leads to pathologic fractures due to abnormal cortical growth and diaphyseal medullary stenosis. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the MTAP gene on chromosome 9p21. Moreover, it is considered to be something that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.
Warfarin resistance is a type of inherited metabolic disorder, defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by a high tolerance for the drug warfarin.

Warfarin sensitivity is a type of autosomal dominant disease and an inherited metabolic disorder, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an inherited metabolic disorder characterized by a low tolerance for the drug warfarin.

Spinal Muscular Atrophy Type 0 is a form of childhood spinal muscular atrophy that begins in childhood, specifically with an onset that starts during childhood. It is defined as a childhood spinal muscular atrophy evident before birth, characterized by diminished movement in the womb, joint deformities, extremely weak muscle tone, and very weak respiratory muscles. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with very severe spinal muscular atrophy.

Posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy 4 is a type of posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a posterior polymorphous corneal dystrophy characterized by an irregular posterior corneal surface with occasional opacities of variable size and shape. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the GRHL2 gene on chromosome 8q22.

Meesmann corneal dystrophy 1 is a type of Meesmann corneal dystrophy and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the presence of numerous microcysts within the anterior epithelium, a condition that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the KRT12 gene on chromosome 17q21. This condition also falls under the category of disorders that have a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Meesmann corneal dystrophy 2 is a subtype of Meesmann corneal dystrophy and an autosomal dominant disease, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Meesmann corneal dystrophy characterized by the fragility of the anterior corneal epithelium, the presence of intraepithelial microcysts, and has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the KRT3 gene on chromosome 12q13.

Fibrochondrogenesis 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of fibrochondrogenesis, characterized by a condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, fibrochondrogenesis 1 is defined by a flat midface with a small nose and anteverted nares, significant shortening of all limb segments but with relatively normal hands and feet, and a small bell-shaped thorax with a protuberant abdomen. This condition has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutations in the COL11A1 gene located on chromosome 1p21.

Fibrochondrogenesis 2 is a type of fibrochondrogenesis and is characterized as an autosomal dominant disease as well as an autosomal recessive disease. It is associated with conditions that have their material basis in either some form of autosomal dominant inheritance or autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, fibrochondrogenesis 2 is defined as a fibrochondrogenesis that has its material basis in homozygous or heterozygous mutation in the COL11A2 gene on chromosome 6p21.3.

Luminal breast carcinoma B is a type of breast carcinoma, which is characterized by low to moderate expression of genes characteristic of luminal epithelial cells including estrogen receptor (ER), and high expression of GGH, LAPTM4B, and CCNE1. Additionally, it has the exact synonym Luminal B Breast Carcinoma.

Stickler Syndrome 2 is a type of Stickler Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a Stickler Syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the COL11A1 gene located on chromosome 1p21.

Stickler syndrome 1 is a type of Stickler syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which specifically has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a Stickler syndrome that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the COL2A1 gene located on chromosome 12q13.

Otospodylomegaepiphyseal dysplasia autosomal dominant is a type of disease that falls under several classifications: it is an autosomal dominant disease, an osteochondrodysplasia, and is characterized by a material basis that involves autosomal dominant inheritance. Additionally, this condition is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia that is characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance of mutations in the COL11A2 gene.

Mucolipidosis III gamma is a type of mucolipidosis and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a mucolipidosis that has its material basis in mutation in the gene encoding the gamma subunit of N-acetylglucosamine-1-phosphotransferase, characterized by short stature, skeletal abnormalities, cardiomegaly, and developmental delay.

Neuronal intestinal dysplasia type A is a type of intestinal pseudo obstruction and it is defined as an intestinal pseudo-obstruction characterized by congenital hypoplasia or aplasia of the sympathetic innervation of the intestine.
Neuronal intestinal dysplasia type B is a type of intestinal pseudo-obstruction and is defined as an intestinal pseudo-obstruction that affects the parasympathetic submucous plexus.

X-linked chronic idiopathic intestinal pseudo-obstruction is a type of intestinal pseudo-obstruction and a form of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as an intestinal pseudo-obstruction that has its material basis in mutations in the FLNA gene located on chromosome Xq28.

Autosomal dominant familial visceral neuropathy is a type of disease characterized by several aspects. Firstly, it falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases. Additionally, it is identified as a type of intestinal pseudo-obstruction. This condition also has a basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, indicating the genetic pattern it follows. The definition of autosomal dominant familial visceral neuropathy further elaborates it as an intestinal pseudo-obstruction that is inherited as an autosomal dominant trait.

Nonsyndromic congenital nail disorder is a type of physical disorder, nail disease, and something that at least has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a nail disease characterized by the underdevelopment of nails.

Diffuse midline glioma H3 K27M mutant is characterized as a type of histone mutated tumor and is also classified as something deriving from glial cells. Specifically, it is defined as a histone mutated tumor characterized by the presence of histone H3 K27M mutation, which is located throughout the midline structures of the central nervous system. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma."
Aortic dissection is a type of aortic disease characterized by the tearing of the intimal layer of the aorta, which results in the separation of the layers of the aortic wall.

Tubular aggregate myopathy 2 is a type of myopathy and also a type of autosomal dominant disease, which is a classification that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is specifically defined as a myopathy characterized by the presence of tubular aggregates in myofibrils, stemming from a heterozygous mutation in the ORAI1 gene on chromosome 12q24. Additionally, tubular aggregate myopathy 2 has a narrower match, ORDO:2593.

Reducing body myopathy 1b is a type of myopathy and an X-linked monogenic disease, which falls under the category of conditions that, at the very least, have a material basis in X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a myopathy characterized by the presence of intracytoplasmic inclusion bodies that are strongly stained by menadione-linked alpha-glycerophosphate dehydrogenase in the absence of its substrate, alpha-glycerophosphate, typically manifesting in late childhood or adulthood. This condition has its material basis in mutations in the FHL1 gene located on chromosome Xq26.
Mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by cell mosaicism, where at least one-quarter of cells have an abnormal number of chromosomes.

Mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome 3 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome, and a type of condition that at least has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a mosaic variegated aneuploidy syndrome that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the TRIP13 gene on chromosome 5p15, resulting in no detectable TRIP13 protein.

RASopathy is a type of syndrome characterized by a syndrome that has its material basis in mutations in genes that alter the Ras subfamily and mitogen-activated protein kinases controlling signal transduction. It is also exactly synonymous with RAS/mitogen-activated protein kinase syndrome.

Noonan syndrome-like disorder with loose anagen hair is a type of RASopathy. This disorder is defined as a RASopathy characterized by several physical attributes and conditions, including macrocephaly, a high forehead, wide-set eyes or hypertelorism, palpebral ptosis, and low-set and posteriorly rotated ears. Additionally, it involves pluckable, sparse, thin, and slow-growing hair, frequent congenital heart defects, darkly pigmented skin with eczema or ichthyosis, short stature, and developmental delay.

Noonan syndrome-like disorder with loose anagen hair 1 is a type of Noonan syndrome-like disorder with loose anagen hair. It is defined as a Noonan-like syndrome with loose anagen hair that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SHOC2 gene located on chromosome 10q25.

Noonan syndrome-like disorder with loose anagen hair 2 is a type of Noonan syndrome-like disorder with loose anagen hair. It is defined as a Noonan syndrome-like disorder with loose anagen hair that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the PPP1CB gene on chromosome 2p23.
Galloway Mowat syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined by developmental delay, progressive microcephaly, cerebral and cerebellar atrophy with extrapyramidal involvement, and optic atrophy.

Burn Mc Keown syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by bilateral choanal atresia, cranio-facial dysmorphism, hearing loss, heart abnormalities, and short stature. It is also known by its exact synonym, Choanal atresia - deafness - cardiac defects - dysmorphism syndrome.

Winchester syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by a loss of bone tissue, particularly in the hands and feet. It falls into a category of conditions that at least have the phenotype of osteolysis.

Opitz GBBB syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized as a congenital midline malformation syndrome, which is marked by hypertelorism, hypospadias, cleft lip/palate, laryngotracheoesophageal abnormalities, imperforate anus, developmental delay, and cardiac defects. The basis of this syndrome is a mutation in the MID1 gene on chromosome Xp22. Additionally, Opitz GBBB syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Opitz G/BBB Syndrome and Opitz GBBB syndrome type I.

Teebi hypertelorism syndrome 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which also falls under the broader category of Teebi hypertelorism syndrome. It is characterized by at least having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by having a material basis in mutations, including a heterozygous mutation in the SPECC1L gene on chromosome 22q11.2 or a heterozygous deletion at chromosome 22q11.2. Moreover, Teebi hypertelorism syndrome 1 is precisely known by several exact synonyms, including Opitz GBBB syndrome type II, SPECC1L-related hypertelorism syndrome, and Teebi hypertelorism syndrome-1.
Glutathione synthetase deficiency is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the lack of glutathione production.

Caudal regression syndrome is a type of physical disorder characterized by impairment of the development of the lower half of the body. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including caudal dysgenesis syndrome, caudal dysplasia sequence, caudal regression sequence, sacral agenesis, and sacral defect with anterior meningocele.

Prothrombin thrombophilia is a type of thrombophilia and an autosomal dominant disease, which is characterized by an increased risk of blood clots, including deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the thrombin gene (F2 gene) on chromosome 11p11. This condition is also described as having a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
Medulloblastoma WNT activated is a type of medulloblastoma that is characterized as a molecular subtype by the activation of the WNT pathway, and TP53 mutations may be present or absent.

Medulloblastoma SHH activated is a type of medulloblastoma and it is defined as a medulloblastoma that is characterized as a molecular subtype by the activation of the sonic hedgehog (SHH) pathway and TP53 mutations that may be present or absent.

Medulloblastoma SHH activated and TP53 mutant is a type of Medulloblastoma SHH activated. It is defined as a molecular subtype of Medulloblastoma SHH activated that is characterized by the activation of the sonic hedgehog (SHH) pathway and the presence of TP53 mutations.

Medulloblastoma SHH activated and TP53 wild type is a specific type of medulloblastoma SHH activated. It is defined as a molecular subtype characterized by the activation of the sonic hedgehog (SHH) pathway and the absence of TP53 mutations. This particular subtype also has an exact synonym, Medulloblastoma SHH-Activated TP53-Wildtype.

Medulloblastoma non-WNT non-SHH is a type of medulloblastoma, defined as a molecular subtype that is not associated with the activation of the WNT pathway or the sonic hedgehog (SHH) pathway, and it lacks TP53 mutations.

Medulloblastoma non-WNT/non-SHH Group 3 is a type of medulloblastoma non-WNT/non-SHH, defined by being a molecular subtype characterized by the absence of TP53 mutations and the possible presence of MYC amplifications.

Medulloblastoma non-WNT/non-SHH group 4 is a type of medulloblastoma non-WNT/non-SHH that is defined as a molecular subtype. It is characterized by the absence of MYC amplifications and TP53 mutations, although abnormalities in chromosome 17 may be present.

NK cell deficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease, defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease that results from a deficiency in the number or function of CD56+CD3 NK cells in peripheral blood.
T cell and NK cell immunodeficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that involves multiple components of the immune system, including both T cell and NK cell deficiencies.

Multisystem inflammatory syndrome in children (MIS-C) is a type of coronavirus infectious disease characterized by a patient aged less than 21 years who presents with fever, laboratory evidence of inflammation, and evidence of clinically severe illness requiring hospitalization, including multisystem organ involvement (such as cardiovascular, dermatologic, gastrointestinal, hematologic, neurologic, renal, or respiratory). This condition occurs in those who have tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 or had exposure to COVID-19. MIS-C is also known by other exact synonyms including multisystem inflammatory disorder in children and adolescents, and paediatric inflammatory multisystemic syndrome.

Gene duplication disease is equivalent to a condition that intersects with both a disease and another condition that arises from at least something having a material basis in a gene and at least something having a material basis in duplication. It is categorized as a type of monogenic disease. Furthermore, gene duplication disease is defined as a monogenic disease resulting from a mutation that leads to the production of one or more copies of a gene. Additionally, gene duplication disease is precisely synonymous with gene duplication syndrome.

Hereditary alpha tryptasemia syndrome is a syndrome and a type of gene duplication disease. It is characterized by its intersection with entities that have a material basis in genes and duplications. Additionally, it derives from mast cells. The syndrome is defined by high blood tryptase levels, resulting from inherited extra copies of the alpha tryptase gene (TPSAB1), affecting multiple organ systems including the skin and connective tissues, as well as the gastrointestinal and cardiovascular systems.

Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathy 82 (DEE82), also known as Early Infantile Epileptic Encephalopathy 82, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and falls under the category of Developmental and Epileptic Encephalopathies. This condition is characterized by seizures in the first year of life, hypotonia, feeding difficulties, severely impaired intellectual development, and global developmental delay. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GOT2 gene on chromosome 16q21, indicating that it arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Infantile liver failure syndrome is a type of syndrome and liver disease, which is specifically located in the liver. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by acute liver failure occurring in the first year of life, manifesting with failure to thrive, hypotonia, moderate global developmental delay, seizures, abnormal liver function tests, microcytic anemia, and elevated serum lactate.

Infantile liver failure syndrome 1 is a type of infantile liver failure syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by an infantile liver failure condition that results from a homozygous mutation in the LARS gene (LARS1) located on chromosome 5q32.

GNE myopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease and myopathy that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness. It is defined as a myopathy characterized by progressive skeletal muscle atrophy, distal muscle weakness, and bilateral foot drop caused by weakness of the anterior tibialis muscles with onset in early adulthood. This condition has its material basis in mutations in the GNE gene, which encodes the rate-limiting enzyme of sialic acid biosynthesis. GNE myopathy is also known by exact synonyms such as Distal Myopathy, Nonaka Type; Hereditary Inclusion Body Myopathy; Nonaka Myopathy; and Inclusion Body Myopathy 2. Furthermore, it has a related synonym, Distal Myopathy with Rimmed Vacuoles, and has an exact match with the MESH identifier C536816.

Congenital Myopathy 6 is a type of congenital myopathy, which is characterized by being both an autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive disease. This condition has a material basis in either autosomal dominant or autosomal recessive inheritance and is notable for having symptoms such as muscle weakness. It is defined as a congenital myopathy characterized by childhood onset of congenital joint contractures, external ophthalmoplegia, and proximal muscle weakness. This condition stems from heterozygous, compound heterozygous, or homozygous mutations in the gene encoding myosin heavy chain IIa (MYHC2A or MYH2) on chromosome 17p13. Additionally, Congenital Myopathy 6 is also known by its exact synonyms, including Inclusion Body Myopathy 3 and Proximal Myopathy and Ophthalmoplegia.

Autosomal dominant congenital deafness with onychodystrophy is a syndrome characterized by congenital deafness and onychodystrophy, with its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ATP6V1B2 gene on chromosome 8p21. It is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, physical disorder, and syndrome that has its foundation in autosomal dominant inheritance and is rooted in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth.

Calvarial doughnut lesions with bone fragility are a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by low bone mineral density, multiple spinal and peripheral fractures beginning in childhood, and sclerotic doughnut-shaped lesions in the cranial bones.

Kenny Caffey Syndrome Type 1 is a type of Kenny Caffey Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which indicates that it has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a Kenny-Caffey syndrome that arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TBCE gene, which encodes the tubulin-specific chaperone E, located on chromosome 1q42.

Kenny Caffey Syndrome Type 2 is a type of Kenny Caffey Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It specifically arises from a heterozygous mutation in the FAM111A gene on chromosome 11q12, categorizing it under conditions with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, Kenny Caffey Syndrome Type 2 is precisely identified with the MESH code: C537020.

Kenny Caffey syndrome is a type of syndrome, osteochondrodysplasia, and a condition that has a phenotype of skeletal dysplasia. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by growth retardation with proportionate short stature, cortical thickening and medullary stenosis of the long bones, delayed anterior fontanelle closure, hypocalcemia due to congenital hypoparathyroidism, and facial dysmorphism, including prominent forehead, microphthalmia, and micrognathia.

Basan syndrome is a type of ectodermal dysplasia, which is defined as an ectodermal dysplasia characterized by neonatal blisters and milia, along with the congenital absence of dermatoglyphics on the hands and feet.

Ehlers Danlos syndrome classic type 2 is a type of Ehlers Danlos syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the collagen alpha-2(V) gene on chromosome 2q31 and is characterized by the absence of widened atrophic scars.

Ehlers-Danlos syndrome arthrochalasia type 1 is a specific type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease, which means it stems from an inheritance pattern that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that is characterized by hypermobility in infants with dislocations of both hips at birth. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COL1A1 gene located on chromosome 17q21.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Arthrochalasia Type 2 is a type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the COL1A2 gene on chromosome 7q21.

Brittle Cornea Syndrome 2 is characterized as a type of autosomal recessive disease, corneal disease, and Ehlers-Danlos syndrome. This syndrome is defined by an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that arises from a homozygous mutation in the PRDM5 gene on chromosome 4q27. It is also described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and is located in the cornea.

Ehlers Danlos syndrome cardiac valvular type is a subtype of Ehlers Danlos syndrome, and it is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. This specific type is characterized by severe issues with the heart valves. The underlying cause of the disease is either homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the COL1A2 gene located on chromosome 7q21. Furthermore, it falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Classic Like 1 is a type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and a type of autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome characterized by hyperextensible skin, hypermobile joints, and tissue fragility, which has its material basis in homozygous or heterozygous mutation in the tenascin-XB gene (TNXB) on chromosome 6p21.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Classic Like 2 is classified as a type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and falls under the broader category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is specifically identified as a condition that inherently arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. The definition of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Classic Like 2 elaborates that it is an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome variant caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the AEBP1 gene located on chromosome 7p13. This condition is characterized by severe joint and skin laxity, osteoporosis affecting the hips and spine, osteoarthritis, soft redundant skin resembling acrogeria, delayed wound healing with abnormal atrophic scarring, and dislocations of shoulders, hips, knees, and ankles.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Dermatosparaxis Type is a specific type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which is characterized by severe skin fragility and sagging, redundant skin. This condition fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Moreover, it is defined by having a mutation in the gene encoding the procollagen protease ADAMTS2 located on chromosome 5q35.

Ehlers Danlos syndrome kyphoscoliotic type 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and is a subtype of Ehlers Danlos syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Ehlers Danlos syndrome kyphoscoliotic type 1 is defined by severe muscle hypotonia at birth, generalized joint laxity, scoliosis at birth, and scleral fragility and rupture of the ocular globe, with its material basis being in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding lysyl hydroxylase (PLOD1) on chromosome 1p36.

Ehlers-Danlos syndrome kyphoscoliotic type 2 is a type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that is marked by severe muscle hypotonia at birth, progressive scoliosis, joint hypermobility, hyperelastic skin, myopathy, sensorineural hearing impairment, and normal pyridinoline excretion in urine. The condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the FKBP14 gene on chromosome 7p15. Additionally, it has an exact match with the OMIM identifier 614557.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Musculocontractural Type 1 is a category of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is also classified as a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is defined by a specific set of characteristics, including distinctive craniofacial dysmorphism, congenital contractures of thumbs and fingers, clubfeet, severe kyphoscoliosis, muscular hypotonia, hyperextensible thin skin with easy bruisability and atrophic scarring, wrinkled palms, joint hypermobility, and ocular involvement. The genetic basis for this syndrome is attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CHST14 gene located on chromosome 15q14.

Ehlers Danlos Syndrome Musculocontractural Type 2 is categorized under autosomal recessive diseases and is a specific type of Ehlers Danlos Syndrome. This syndrome is associated with autosomal recessive inheritance and manifests symptoms such as muscle weakness. It is defined by its progressive multisystem fragility-related manifestations, which include joint dislocations and deformities, skin hyperextensibility, bruisability, and fragility leading to recurrent large subcutaneous hematomas, as well as complications in cardiac valvular, respiratory, gastrointestinal, and ophthalmologic systems. Additionally, it features myopathy characterized by muscle hypoplasia, muscle weakness, and an abnormal muscle fiber pattern in histology during adulthood, resulting in gross motor developmental delay. The material basis for this syndrome is a homozygous mutation in the DSE gene located on chromosome 6q22.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome Spondylodysplastic Type 1 is characterized as a type of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome and falls under autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined by specific features including short stature, developmental anomalies of the forearm bones and elbow, bowing of extremities, alongside the classic signs of Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome such as joint laxity, skin hyperextensibility, and poor wound healing. These characteristics are attributed to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the B4GALT7 gene located on chromosome 5q35. This syndrome also exemplifies a condition with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Ehlers-Danlos syndrome spondylodysplastic type 3 is a type of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome that is characterized by having its material basis in homozygous mutation in the zinc transporter gene SLC39A13 on chromosome 11p11. This condition is characterized by short stature, hyperelastic skin and hypermobile joints, protuberant eyes with bluish sclerae, finely wrinkled palms, and distinctive radiologic features.

Libman Sacks endocarditis is a type of endocarditis and an autoimmune disease of the cardiovascular system, which is characterized by a phenotype that includes at least some abnormal immunoglobulin level. It is defined as an endocarditis characterized by Libman-Sacks vegetations, commonly seen in patients with systemic lupus erythematosus, and is frequently complicated with embolic cerebrovascular disease. Moreover, it has exact synonyms, including LibmannSachs and Endocarditis in systemic lupus erythematosus.

Limbic encephalitis is a type of encephalitis and an autoimmune disease of the central nervous system. It is characterized by a subacute onset of short-term memory deficits, seizures, or psychiatric symptoms, which are located in the medial temporal lobes. Additionally, limbic encephalitis is associated with some abnormal immunoglobulin level phenotype, has seizures as a symptom, and is a disease that affects the temporal lobe.

Autoimmune cholangitis is a type of autoimmune hepatitis characterized by primary biliary cirrhosis clinical, biochemical, and histologic characteristics with antinuclear antibody-positive sera. It is also exactly synonymous with autoimmune cholangiopathy.
Transverse myelitis is a type of myelitis that is defined as a myelitis characterized by a band-like sensation across the trunk of the body, with sensory changes below.

Antisynthetase syndrome is a type of autoimmune disease that is characterized by myositis, arthralgia, Raynaud phenomenon, mechanic hands, interstitial lung disease, and serum autoantibodies to aminoacyl transfer RNA synthetases. Furthermore, antisynthetase syndrome has an exact match with MESH:C537778.

Polymyositis is a type of autoimmune disease of the musculoskeletal system and a type of myositis. It is characterized by a condition that at least has the phenotype of abnormal immunoglobulin level and presents with symptoms such as muscle weakness. Moreover, polymyositis is defined as a myositis that is characterized by muscle weakness affecting both sides of your body.

Sweet syndrome is a type of allergic disease, a type of skin disease, and a type of condition that at least has symptoms of some allergic reactions. It is defined as a skin disease characterized by the sudden onset of well-defined tender plaques or nodules accompanied by fever, arthralgias, ocular inflammation, headaches, and, rarely, oral or genital lesions. Sweet syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms, Acute Febrile Neutrophilic Dermatosis and Sweet's syndrome.
Chronic urticaria is a type of urticaria characterized by the presence of urticaria for a period exceeding 6 weeks, assuming symptoms for most days of the week.

Chronic inducible urticaria is a type of chronic urticaria defined as a chronic condition characterized by a history of a consistent stimulus that initiates lesions. These lesions are typically short-lived and fleeting, lasting from a few minutes up to 2 hours.

Chronic spontaneous urticaria is a type of chronic urticaria, which is defined as a chronic urticaria characterized by urticaria independent of any exogenous stimulus. It also has the exact synonym chronic idiopathic urticaria.

Erythema nodosum is a type of panniculitis and is defined as a panniculitis characterized by the sudden onset of painful, erythematous, subcutaneous nodules mainly localized to the pretibial areas. The lesions are usually bilateral and symmetrical, ranging from 1 to 5 cm in diameter.

Keratosis pilaris atrophicans is a type of autosomal recessive disease and ichthyosis, characterized by a basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an ichthyosis that involves perifollicular keratosis and inflammation, which progresses to atrophy and scarring of the facial skin.
Keratosis Pilaris Atrophicans Faciei is a type of Keratosis Pilaris Atrophicans, defined by scar-like follicular depressions and loss of hair, primarily in the eyebrow area.

Keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans is a type of keratosis pilaris atrophicans, which is defined as a keratosis pilaris atrophicans characterized by scarring alopecia of the scalp, eyebrows, and axillae, and it is sometimes associated with photophobia and keratoderma.

X-linked keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans is a specific type of keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans and falls under the category of X-linked recessive diseases. It is characterized by a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. Furthermore, this condition is defined as a keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans that has a material basis in a mutation in the MBTPS2 gene.

Autosomal dominant keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans is a type of keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans, defined as a keratosis follicularis spinulosa decalvans that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Atrophoderma vermiculata is a type of keratosis pilaris atrophicans and is defined as a keratosis pilaris atrophicans that typically presents in childhood with erythema and follicular keratotic papules. These slowly progress to characteristic atrophy, described as worm-eaten, reticular, or honeycomb, and occurs on the cheeks, preauricular area, and forehead.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 1 is a type of Fanconi syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is defined as a Fanconi syndrome that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GATM gene on chromosome 15q21. This condition is also categorized as a type of disorder that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 2 is a type of Fanconi syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome has a definition as a Fanconi syndrome that arises from a homozygous mutation in the SLC34A1 gene located on chromosome 5q35.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 3 is a type of Fanconi syndrome and a form of autosomal dominant disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Fanconi syndrome characterized by rickets, impaired growth, glucosuria, generalized aminoaciduria, phosphaturia, metabolic acidosis, and low molecular weight proteinuria, which has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the EHHADH gene on chromosome 3q27.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of Fanconi syndrome, which is characterized by a condition that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Fanconi syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the HNF4A gene on chromosome 20q13.

Fanconi renotubular syndrome 5 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and Fanconi syndrome, which also falls under the category of conditions with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a Fanconi syndrome characterized by proximal renotubular dysfunction from birth, followed by progressive kidney disease and pulmonary fibrosis, and is caused by a homozygous mutation in the NDUFAF6 gene located on chromosome 8q22. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with Acadian-variant Fanconi syndrome.

Autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy type 2z is a type of autosomal recessive limb girdle muscular dystrophy that at least has symptoms of muscle weakness and progressive weakness. It is defined as an autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy characterized by young-adult onset of slowly progressive proximal upper and lower limb muscle weakness and atrophy, which has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the POGLUT1 gene on chromosome 3q13. Additionally, it has the exact synonym limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 21.
Diffuse gastric cancer is a type of stomach cancer, which is defined as a stomach cancer characterized by the development of diffuse (signet ring cell) gastric cancer underneath the stomach lining.

Hereditary diffuse gastric cancer is a type of autosomal dominant and diffuse gastric cancer, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a diffuse gastric cancer characterized by the development of diffuse (signet ring cell) gastric cancer at a young age, and is associated with germline heterozygous mutations of the CDH1, MAP3K6, and CTNNA1 genes.

Autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder 72 is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is defined as an autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the METTL5 gene on chromosome 2q31. Additionally, autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder 72 is exactly synonymous with autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder-72 and autosomal recessive mental retardation 72.

Erythrokeratodermia variabilis et progressiva 6 is a subtype of erythrokeratodermia variabilis and an autosomal dominant disease, which inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an erythrokeratodermia variabilis characterized by the development of erythematous hyperkeratotic plaques within the first year of life. These plaques initially appear on distal extremities and progressively involve the face, wrists, and ankles, while sparing volar surfaces. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the TRPM4 gene located on chromosome 19q13.

Autoimmune myocarditis is a type of autoimmune disease of the cardiovascular system, which is characterized by inflammation of the heart muscle. This condition is also a type of myocarditis. Moreover, autoimmune myocarditis falls under the category of conditions that intersect with those having at least one symptom of inflammation and diseases that are located in the myocardium.

Pyridoxine dependent epilepsy is a type of epilepsy and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls under the category of conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as an epilepsy characterized by intractable seizures occurring within the first weeks to months of life, which are not controlled by antiepileptic drugs but respond both clinically and electrographically to large daily supplements of pyridoxine. Moreover, pyridoxine dependent epilepsy is closely matched with UMLS_CUI:C1849508 and has exact matches with several medical databases and classifications including GARD:9298, MESH:C536254, ORDO:3006, and SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:734434007.

Early onset vitamin B6 dependent epilepsy 1 is a type of pyridoxine dependent epilepsy, which also falls under the category of conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibit a phenotype characterized by some abnormality of vitamin B metabolism. This condition is defined as a pyridoxine-dependent epilepsy that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the PLPBP gene on chromosome 8p11.23. It is broadly synonymous with early-onset vitamin B6-dependent epilepsy and has exact synonyms EPEO1 and PDE-PLPBP. Moreover, early onset vitamin B6 dependent epilepsy 1 has an exact match with OMIM:617290.

Autosomal dominant beta thalassemia is a specific form of beta thalassemia and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a type of condition that fundamentally involves autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a beta thalassemia that arises from a single dominantly inherited mutated HBB gene, leading to signs and symptoms associated with beta-thalassemia major or beta-thalassemia intermedia. Additionally, autosomal dominant beta thalassemia is also precisely known as inclusion body beta-thalassemia.

Beta thalassemia major is a type of beta thalassemia and a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by severe anemia and an enlarged liver and spleen before the age of 2 years. Beta thalassemia major is also exactly synonymous with Cooley's anemia.

Beta thalassemia intermedia is a type of beta thalassemia and a type of condition that has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a beta thalassemia characterized by mild to moderate anemia, alongside slow growth and bone abnormalities that appear in early childhood or later in life.

Delta beta thalassemia is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of beta thalassemia, which is characterized by something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a beta thalassemia that is characterized by decreased or absent synthesis of both the delta- and beta-globin chains, leading to a compensatory increase in fetal gamma-chain synthesis. This disorder results in a microcytic anemia that is clinically mild.

Thalassemia minor is a type of beta thalassemia defined as a beta thalassemia that has a material basis in one HBB gene mutation without typical thalassemia symptoms, but may have some symptoms of anemia.

Complete androgen insensitivity syndrome is a type of androgen insensitivity syndrome that is defined by its characteristic of complete androgen insensitivity, meaning the body cannot utilize androgens at all. Individuals with this condition exhibit the external sex characteristics of females but do not have a uterus.

Partial Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome (PAIS) is a type of Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome that has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance, positioning it as a type of X-linked recessive disease. PAIS is characterized by a 46,XY karyotype with testes that produce age-appropriate androgen levels, but due to defects in androgen action, the external genitalia are undermasculinized. Additionally, PAIS is also exactly synonymous with Reifenstein syndrome.

Lung sarcomatoid carcinoma is a type of lung carcinoma characterized by the presence of a sarcomatoid component often associated with giant cell differentiation. It is also exactly synonymous with "Sarcomatoid carcinoma of the lung" and "pulmonary sarcomatoid carcinoma."

Transient infantile liver failure is a type of liver disease and an autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by elevated liver enzymes, jaundice, vomiting, coagulopathy, and hyperbilirubinemia, along with the presence of increased serum lactate. This condition at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and is specifically associated with homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TRMU gene, which plays a role in mitochondrial protein translation, located on chromosome 22q13.

Plasmablastic lymphoma is a subtype of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, which is defined as a diffuse large B-cell lymphoma characterized by the presence of large neoplastic cells resembling B-immunoblasts and having the immunophenotypic profile of plasma cells.
Acute erythroid leukemia is a type of acute myeloid leukemia and it is defined as an acute myeloid leukemia that is characterized by a predominant immature erythroid population.

A benign exocrine pancreas neoplasm is the same as an entity that intersects with both a benign neoplasm and a disease, which is located at the exocrine pancreas. It is also a type of benign neoplasm of the endocrine organ. Additionally, a benign exocrine pancreas neoplasm is defined as an endocrine organ benign neoplasm that arises from the exocrine pancreas.

Mucinous pancreas adenocarcinoma is a type of mucinous adenocarcinoma and also a type of pancreatic adenocarcinoma. It is classified as a condition that derives from an intersection of epithelial cells and glands that originate from mucous glands. Furthermore, it is defined as a pancreatic adenocarcinoma that originates from epithelial cells in glandular tissue, which produce mucin.

Urinary tract infection (UTI) is a type of bacterial infectious disease and a type of urinary system disease, which specifically originates from bacteria. It is characterized by an infection in any part of the urinary system, including the kidneys, ureters, bladder, or urethra. Additionally, "UTI" is an exact synonym for urinary tract infection, and it has an exact match with the MESH identifier D014552.

Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere Syndrome 1 is classified under various categories: it is a type of Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere Syndrome, a type of autosomal recessive disease, and a condition that fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a specific form of Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere syndrome characterized by progressive bulbar palsy with sensorineural deafness, with its material basis being homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the C20ORF54 gene (SLC52A3) located on chromosome 20p13.

Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere Syndrome 2 is a specific type of Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere Syndrome, and it is also classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance and displays symptoms including muscle weakness. Specifically, Brown-Vialetto-Van Laere Syndrome 2 is defined as a condition that emerges in early childhood, marked by sensorineural deafness, bulbar dysfunction, and severe, diffuse muscle weakness and wasting affecting the upper and lower limbs as well as axial muscles. This leads to respiratory insufficiency. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC52A2 gene located on chromosome 8q24.

Proximal symphalangism 1 is a specific type of proximal symphalangism. It is defined as a form of proximal symphalangism characterized by ankylosis of the proximal interphalangeal joints, fusion of carpal and tarsal bones, and, in some instances, conductive deafness. This condition arises due to a heterozygous mutation in the NOG gene located on chromosome 17q22.

Proximal symphalangism 2 is a specific type of proximal symphalangism, characterized by the absence of the cuboid bone, lack of shortness of the first and fifth metacarpal bones, and the presence of distal interphalangeal joint fusions and flat feet. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the GDF5 gene located on chromosome 20q11.

Treacher Collins Syndrome 1 is a type of Treacher Collins Syndrome and is also categorized under conditions that at least have a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a Treacher Collins Syndrome that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the 'treacle' gene (TCOF1) on chromosome 5q32.

Treacher Collins Syndrome 2 is a type of Treacher Collins Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by a heterozygous mutation in the POLR1D gene on chromosome 13q12.

Treacher Collins Syndrome 3 is a type of Treacher Collins Syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by a compound heterozygous mutation in the POLR1C gene located on chromosome 6p21.

Treacher Collins Syndrome 4 is a type of Treacher Collins Syndrome, characterized by craniofacial dysmorphisms such as downslanting palpebral fissures, malar and mandibular hypoplasia, and microtia. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the POLR1B gene on chromosome 2q14.

Childhood acute megakaryoblastic leukemia is a type of acute megakaryocytic leukemia and is also known as pediatric non-Down syndrome acute megakaryoblastic leukemia. This type of leukemia begins during childhood onset. It is characterized by fusion oncogenes involving transcriptional regulators in childhood, defining it as an acute megakaryocytic leukemia.
Acute basophilic leukemia is a type of acute myeloid leukemia that is characterized by primary differentiation to basophils.

Core binding factor acute myeloid leukemia is a type of acute myeloid leukemia characterized by the presence of t(8;21)(q22;q22) or inv(16)(p13q22)/t(16;16)(p13;q22). These cytogenetic abnormalities disrupt the transcription factor CBF, a regulator of normal hematopoiesis.

Nasal type extranodal NK T cell lymphoma is a type of mature T cell and NK cell lymphoma, as well as a type of nasal cavity cancer. It is defined as a mature T-cell and NK-cell lymphoma characterized by an often angiocentric and angiodestructive cellular infiltrate composed of EBV positive NK/T cells. Additionally, it falls under the category of diseases located in the nasal cavity.

Myeloid leukemia associated with Down syndrome is a type of acute megakaryocytic leukemia, which is defined as an acute megakaryocytic leukemia occurring in children with Down syndrome. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the GATA1 gene.

Sinonasal undifferentiated carcinoma is a type of paranasal sinus cancer and a type of nasal cavity carcinoma. It is also a type of condition where the disease is located in the paranasal sinus. It is defined as a nasal cavity carcinoma that originates from the sinonasal tract and is characterized by the presence of small to medium-sized malignant cells.

Salivary gland mucinous adenocarcinoma is a type of salivary gland carcinoma and also a type of mucinous adenocarcinoma. It falls under a category that at least derives from an intersection involving epithelial cells and entities that originate from mucous glands. Additionally, salivary gland mucinous adenocarcinoma is defined as a salivary gland carcinoma characterized by the presence of large pools of extracellular mucin, within which clusters of malignant epithelial cells are found.

Autosomal dominant craniometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of disease characterized by autosomal dominant inheritance and falls under the broader category of craniometaphyseal dysplasia. This particular condition arises from a heterozygous mutation in the ANKH gene located on chromosome 5p15, which serves as its material basis.

Autosomal recessive craniometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of craniometaphyseal dysplasia. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a craniometaphyseal dysplasia that arises from a homozygous mutation in the GJA1 gene located on chromosome 6q22.
Cranioectodermal dysplasia 1 is a type of cranioectodermal dysplasia, defined as having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IFT122 gene on chromosome 3q21.

Cranioectodermal dysplasia 2 is a specific type of cranioectodermal dysplasia, characterized by a definition that includes its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the WDR35 gene located on chromosome 2p24.

Cranioectodermal dysplasia 3 is a type of cranioectodermal dysplasia and is defined as a cranioectodermal dysplasia that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the IFT43 gene on chromosome 14q24.

Cranioectodermal dysplasia 4 is a type of cranioectodermal dysplasia and is defined as a cranioectodermal dysplasia that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the WDR19 gene on chromosome 4p14.

Autosomal dominant craniodiaphyseal dysplasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease, craniodiaphyseal dysplasia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a craniodiaphyseal dysplasia that has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the SOST gene on chromosome 17q21.

Mammary analogue secretory carcinoma is a type of salivary gland carcinoma, defined as a salivary gland carcinoma that has a material basis in a chromosomal translocation resulting in an ETV6-NTRK3 fusion gene.
Chronic asthma is a type of asthma that is defined by the development of persistent airway inflammation and recurrent attacks of breathlessness and wheezing, which vary in severity and frequency.

Acute asthma is a type of asthma defined by a severe and sudden onset of symptoms, including increasing wheezing, airways closing, smooth muscle contraction, mucus plugging, and lower airway edema, which may be reversible upon treatment.

Extrinsic asthma is recognized as a chronic, allergic disease, which can be transmitted through airborne means and often presents symptoms such as allergic reactions. It is defined as a chronic asthma that is set off by an allergen, marked by an immune system overreaction to innocuous substances like pollen or dust, leading to the release of immunoglobin E (IgE) antibodies. Furthermore, extrinsic asthma is precisely synonymous with atopic asthma.

Intermittent asthma is a type of chronic asthma characterized by its severity with symptoms manifesting two or fewer days per week, nighttime awakenings occurring two or fewer times per month, the use of short-acting beta agonist for symptom control needed two or fewer days per week, and no interference with normal activity.

Persistent mild asthma is a type of chronic asthma that is defined by its severity, characterized by symptoms occurring two or more days per week, nighttime awakenings three to four times per month, the use of short-acting beta agonist for symptom control two or more days per week, and minor limitation of normal activity.

Persistent moderate asthma is a type of chronic asthma, defined as a chronic asthma characterized by daily symptoms, nighttime awakenings more than once per week, daily use of short-acting beta agonist for symptom control, and some limitation of normal activity.

Childhood onset asthma is a type of chronic asthma and something that starts during early childhood. It is defined as a chronic asthma characterized by its first presentation in early childhood. Additionally, it has an exact synonym, which is childhood asthma.

Adult onset severe asthma is a type of chronic asthma that begins in adulthood. It is defined as a chronic asthma characterized by its first presentation in adulthood, highlighting that its existence starts during adult onset.

T2 high asthma is a type of chronic asthma that is defined as a chronic asthma characterized by the pathophysiology phenotype combination (endotype) of early-onset allergic asthma, late-onset eosinophilic asthma, and aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease. Additionally, it has the exact synonym "type 2 high endotype."

T2 low asthma is a type of chronic asthma that is defined as a chronic asthma characterized by a pathophysiology phenotype combination (endotype) of non-atopic, smoking, obesity-related, and elderly. It is further characterized by neutrophilic (sputum neutrophils > 4060%) or paucigranulocytic (i.e., normal sputum levels of both eosinophils and neutrophils) inflammation and a lack of response to corticosteroid therapy. Additionally, T2 low asthma has an exact synonym, which is the type 2 low endotype.

Environmental induced asthma is a type of intrinsic asthma and has the exact synonym irritant asthma. It is defined as an intrinsic asthma that is characterized by exposure to tobacco smoke and other inflammatory gases or particulate matter.
Occupational asthma is a type of environmental induced asthma characterized by a variable airflow limitation due to exposure to inhaled irritants in the workplace.

Exercise-induced bronchoconstriction is a type of intrinsic asthma and has the definition of an intrinsic asthma that is characterized by the narrowing of the airways during or shortly after exercise. Furthermore, it has the exact synonym "exercise-induced asthma".

Aspirin-induced respiratory disease is a type of intrinsic asthma and has an exact synonym, aspirin-sensitive asthma. It is defined as an intrinsic asthma that is characterized by severe and prolonged airway obstruction after the ingestion of aspirin or other non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.
