Near fatal asthma is a type of acute asthma, which is defined as an acute asthma characterized by a respiratory arrest or arterial carbon dioxide tension greater than 50 mmHg, with or without altered consciousness, necessitating mechanical ventilation.

Persistent severe asthma is a type of chronic asthma that is defined by its severity. It is characterized by symptoms that occur two or fewer days per week, nighttime awakenings that happen two or fewer times per month, the need to use short-acting beta agonist for symptom control several times per day, and extremely limited normal activity.

Thunderstorm-triggered asthma is a type of allergic asthma, which is defined as an allergic asthma characterized by acute asthma attacks immediately following a thunderstorm resulting from the inhalation of high concentrations of aeroallergens, most commonly grass pollen. It also has exact synonyms, including thunderstorm asthma and thunderstorm-related asthma.

Nocturnal asthma is a type of chronic asthma defined by a significant decline in pulmonary function and an increase in airway inflammation at night. This condition is characterized by various overnight physiological abnormalities during sleep, such as increased airway inflammation and decreased steroid responsiveness, increased pulmonary capillary blood volume, and functional differences in blood/air volume ratios. Additionally, the recumbent posture adopted during sleep leads to a reduction in lung volumes, respiratory muscle tone, and lung compliance, contributing to mechanical coupling of the parenchyma to the airways.
Human cytomegalovirus infection is a type of viral infectious disease. It is defined as a viral infectious disease that has a material basis in Human betaherpesvirus 5.

Vexas syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by blood clots in veins, recurrent fevers, pulmonary abnormalities, and vacuoles in myeloid cells. It has a material basis in a mutation in the UBA1 gene on chromosome Xp11. Furthermore, Vexas syndrome is exactly synonymous with vacuoles, E1 enzyme, X-linked, autoinflammatory, and somatic syndrome.

Low grade glioma, also known exactly as benign glioma, is defined as a cell type benign neoplasm that has its material basis in glial cells, including astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, or ependymocytes. It is essentially a benign neoplasm that intersects with both conditions derived from some glial cell and diseases located in the brain and spinal cord. This means low grade glioma is categorized under several types: a type of cell type benign neoplasm, a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm, a type of spinal cord disease, a type of brain disease, a type of entity that at least derives from some glial cell, and a type of disease having its location in the central nervous system.

Childhood low grade glioma is a type of low grade glioma that specifically begins during childhood onset. It is defined as a low-grade glioma occurring in children and includes tumors of astrocytic, oligodendroglial, and mixed glial-neuronal histology. Additionally, childhood low grade glioma is exactly synonymous with pediatric low-grade glioma.
Subjective cognitive decline is a type of cognitive disorder characterized by the presence of significant and persistent cognitive complaints.

Mild cognitive impairment is a type of cognitive disorder, defined as a cognitive disorder that is characterized by objective impairment in cognition with minimal impairment of their capacity to undertake the instrumental activities of daily living.

Laryngomalacia is a type of physical disorder and a specific kind of laryngeal disease, which is characterized by the inward collapse of flaccid supraglottic structures during inspiration. It is notably identified by noisy breathing (stridor), a symptom that becomes more pronounced when the infant is either on their back or crying. This condition is also known as congenital laryngomalacia and has a unique identifier, MESH:D055092, indicating its classification within medical databases. The disease primarily stems from abnormalities in prenatal development or birth.
Acquired laryngomalacia is a type of laryngeal disease that is defined as a laryngeal disease characterized by acquired collapse of laryngeal suprastructures.

Torch syndrome is a type of physical disorder, a syndrome, and something that, at minimum, has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital infection with toxoplasmosis, rubella, cytomegalovirus, herpes simplex, and other organisms.

Growth hormone insensitivity syndrome with immune dysregulation 1 is a type of syndrome that falls under autosomal recessive diseases. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by short stature due to insensitivity to growth hormone, which has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the STAT5B gene on chromosome 17q21. This condition is also an example of a disorder that arises from autosomal recessive inheritance.

Growth hormone insensitivity syndrome with immune dysregulation 2 is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is characterized by a type of condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This specific syndrome is defined by a short stature resulting from insensitivity to growth hormone, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the STAT5B gene located on chromosome 17q21.

X-linked warfarin sensitivity is a type of inherited metabolic disorder characterized by bleeding complications when given warfarin for anticoagulation. This condition has a material basis in variation in the F9 gene located on chromosome Xq27.

Optic atrophy 12 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of optic atrophy, which is characterized by a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It has a definition as an optic atrophy that is characterized by slowly progressive visual impairment, typically beginning in the first decade of life, and it has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the AFG3L2 gene on chromosome 18p11.

Pemphigoid is an autoimmune disease affecting the skin and connective tissue, which is classified as a type of bullous skin disease. It is characterized by an intersection of dermatitis and conditions that exhibit the symptom of blister formation. Specifically, pemphigoid is defined as an autoimmune condition of the skin and connective tissue characterized by subepidermal blistering, particularly in the lower abdomen, groin, and flexor surfaces of the extremities, resulting in tense blisters that do not break easily.
Intracranial meningioma, which is a type of meningioma, is defined as a meningioma that arises within the cranial cavity.
Supratentorial meningioma is a type of meningioma that is defined as a meningioma affecting the supratentorial brain.

Omodysplasia 1 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a specific form of omodysplasia. It is characterized by a severe congenital condition known as micromelia, where there is shortening and distal tapering of the humeri and femora, giving them a club-like appearance. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GPC6 gene located on chromosome 13q32. It falls under the category of diseases that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Omodysplasia 2 is a type of omodysplasia and also a type of autosomal dominant disease, which implies it is something that at least has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an omodysplasia characterized by shortened humeri, dislocated radial heads, shortened first metacarpals, craniofacial dysmorphism, and variable genitourinary anomalies. This condition has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FZD2 gene on chromosome 17q21.

Latent autoimmune diabetes in adults (LADA) is a type of Type 1 diabetes mellitus that is also characterized by a less intensive autoimmune process, highly variable -cell destruction, different degrees of insulin resistance, and heterogeneous titre and pattern of islet autoantibody, sharing features with both type 1 and type 2 diabetes mellitus. It is defined as a type of diabetes that at least has the phenotype of some abnormal immunoglobulin level and its existence starts during adult onset. Furthermore, LADA is exactly synonymous with type 1.5 diabetes and LADA, and it has an exact match with MESH:D000071698.

Long COVID is a type of Coronavirus infectious disease that is characterized by long-term persistent and fluctuating symptoms in individuals with COVID-19, persisting beyond three to four weeks. It includes symptoms such as confusion, headache, tachycardia, memory loss, chest pain, dizziness, breathing problems, fatigue, ageusia (loss of the ability to smell and taste), and concentration difficulty. Long COVID also has exact synonyms: PASC, chronic COVID-19, post-COVID syndrome, and post-acute sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 infection.

Ocular motor apraxia Cogan type is a type of eye disease that is characterized by defective or absent horizontal voluntary eye movements, and defective or absent horizontal ocular attraction movements.
Pemphigus foliaceus is a type of pemphigus that is characterized by blistering lesions on otherwise healthy-looking skin. It is also exactly known as pemphigus foliaceous.

IgA pemphigus is a type of pemphigus characterized by painful and pruritic vesiculopustular eruptions. These eruptions form due to circulating IgA antibodies against keratinocyte cell surface components, which are responsible for cell-to-cell adherence.
Paraneoplastic pemphigus is a type of pemphigus characterized by painful blisters and denuded areas of the mouth, lips, esophagus, and skin.

Anaplastic pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma is a type of malignant astrocytoma, which is defined as a malignant astrocytoma characterized by the presence of five or more mitoses per 10 high-power fields.
Parkinsonism is a type of movement disease defined as a movement disorder that is characterized by disturbances of balance, gait, and posture.

Vascular parkinsonism is a type of parkinsonism that is defined as a form of parkinsonism characterized by postural instability, a broad-based gait, and the absence of tremors, all of which are of vascular origin.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 1 is a type of X-linked monogenic disease and also falls under the category of primary ovarian insufficiency. It is characterized by having a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that originates from premutations in the FMR1 gene located on chromosome Xq27.3, within the region designated as POF1 (Xq26-q28). Furthermore, primary ovarian insufficiency 1 is precisely referred to as FMR1-related primary ovarian insufficiency, Fragile X-associated primary ovarian insufficiency, and premature ovarian failure 1.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 2a is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and a specific type of X-linked dominant disease, which at least has a material basis in some X-linked dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has a material basis in a mutation in the DIAPH2 gene on chromosome Xq22.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 2b is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and is also categorized as a type of X-linked recessive disease, indicating that it is a condition that at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has its material basis in a mutation in the POF1B gene.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 3 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this condition is defined by a primary ovarian insufficiency that results from a heterozygous mutation in the FOXL2 gene located on chromosome 3q22.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 4 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an X-linked monogenic disease that at least has a material basis in X-linked inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that is caused by a mutation in the BMP15 gene on chromosome Xp11.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 5 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal dominant disease that specifically has its material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that results from a heterozygous mutation in the NOBOX gene on chromosome 7q35.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 6 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, this primary ovarian insufficiency is defined by having a material basis in either a heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the FIGLA gene located on chromosome 2p13.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 7 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Specifically, it is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the NR5A1 gene located on chromosome 9q33.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of primary ovarian insufficiency, which has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the STAG3 gene on chromosome 7q22.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 9 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has its material basis in a compound heterozygous mutation in the HFM1 gene on chromosome 1p22.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 10 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency characterized by primary amenorrhea, hypergonadotropic ovarian insufficiency, and genomic instability in somatic cells, with its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MCM8 gene on chromosome 20p.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 11 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of primary ovarian insufficiency. It is characterized by secondary amenorrhea and hypergonadotropic ovarian insufficiency, with elevated serum follicle-stimulating hormone levels before age 40 years. This condition has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance and specifically has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the ERCC6 gene on chromosome 10q11.

Primary Ovarian Insufficiency 12 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, a type of primary ovarian insufficiency, and a type of condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SYCE1 gene on chromosome 10q26. Additionally, Primary Ovarian Insufficiency 12 has an exact match with OMIM:616947.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 13 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal recessive disease, which specifically involves a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the MSH5 gene on chromosome 6p21.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 14 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and an autosomal recessive disease, which also falls into the category of disorders that at least have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the GDF9 gene located on chromosome 5q31.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 15 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of primary ovarian insufficiency, which fundamentally has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency that manifests through oligomenorrhea starting in the third decade of life, accompanied by small ovaries, a reduced number of follicles, and elevated gonadotropic hormones. This condition is specifically attributed to a homozygous mutation in the FANCM gene located on chromosome 14q21.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 16 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency and a type of autosomal dominant disease, which essentially has a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency characterized by the onset of amenorrhea early in the fourth decade of life, accompanied by elevated follicle-stimulating hormone levels and low estradiol levels. This condition specifically has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the BNC1 gene located on chromosome 15q25.

Primary ovarian insufficiency 17 is a type of primary ovarian insufficiency. It is defined as a primary ovarian insufficiency characterized by the early cessation of menses after initial menarche, accompanied by small ovaries and uterus. This condition has a material basis in a homozygous mutation in the XRCC2 gene located on chromosome 7q36.
IDH mutant anaplastic astrocytoma is a type of anaplastic astrocytoma defined as an anaplastic astrocytoma carrying IDH mutations.
IDH wildtype anaplastic astrocytoma is a type of anaplastic astrocytoma defined as an anaplastic astrocytoma that lacks mutations in the IDH1 or IDH2 genes.

Astrocytoma IDH mutant grade 4 is a type of IDH mutant anaplastic astrocytoma, defined as an IDH-mutant anaplastic astrocytoma that is characterized by the presence of necrosis and/or microvascular proliferation or homozygous deletion of CDKN2A and/or CDKN2B genes. It is noted that the term glioblastoma no longer applies to central nervous system WHO grade 4 IDH-mutant astrocytomas.

IDH wildtype glioblastoma is a type of glioblastoma that is defined as a glioblastoma characterized by high cellularity, high mitotic activity, necrosis or microvascular proliferation, and that lacks mutations in IDH genes.

A histone mutated tumor, also exactly known as a histone mutated tumour, is a type of high-grade glioma. It is defined as a high-grade glioma that has its material basis in mutations in the genes encoding histones.
Diffuse glioma H3 G34 mutant is a type of histone mutated tumor, which is defined as a histone mutated tumor that has its material basis in mutations in codon 34 of the H3 histone family 3A protein.

Pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma BRAF mutant is a type of anaplastic pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma, which is defined as an anaplastic pleomorphic xanthoastrocytoma that has a material basis in BRAF mutations.

IDH mutant and 1p 19q codeleted oligodendroglioma is a type of anaplastic oligodendroglioma, which is defined as an anaplastic oligodendroglioma that has a material basis in IDH gene family mutation and combined whole-arm losses of 1p and 19q (1p/19q codeletion). It has the exact synonyms "Oligodendroglioma, IDH-mutant and 1p/19q-codeleted" and "anaplastic oligodendroglioma, IDH-mutant and 1p/19q-codeleted."

Vitamin D dependent rickets is a type of bone development disease and also a type of hematopoietic system disease, indicating that this disease affects the hematopoietic system. This condition is defined as a bone development disease characterized by the softening and weakening of the bones, hypocalcemia, high levels of parathyroid hormone, and hypophosphatemia.

Vitamin D-dependent rickets type 2a is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a specific form of vitamin D-dependent rickets. It is characterized by abnormally high levels of calcitriol and has its material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding the vitamin D receptor (VDR) on chromosome 12q. This condition is also a type of disease that, at the very least, has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Vitamin D dependent rickets type 2b is a type of vitamin D dependent rickets, defined as a vitamin D-dependent rickets characterized by the abnormal expression of a hormone response element-binding protein that interferes with the normal function of the vitamin D receptor.

Vitamin D-dependent rickets type 1a is a type of vitamin D-dependent rickets and an autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by a specific condition that inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This particular type of rickets is defined by abnormally low levels of calcitriol, resulting from mutations in the gene encoding 25-hydroxyvitamin D3-1-alpha-hydroxylase (CYP27B1) located on chromosome 12q13.

Vitamin D-dependent rickets type 1b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a specific form of vitamin D-dependent rickets. It is characterized as a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, vitamin D-dependent rickets type 1b is defined as a vitamin D-dependent rickets that is marked by abnormally low levels of calcitriol. This condition has its material basis in homozygous, compound heterozygous, or heterozygous mutations in the CYP2R1 gene located on chromosome 11p15.

Spinal ependymoma MYCN amplified is a type of spinal cord ependymoma that is characterized by MYCN amplification. It has the exact synonyms Spinal Cord Ependymoma, MYCN Amplified and spinal ependymoma, MYCN.
Posterior fossa ependymoma is a high-grade ependymoma that is located within the posterior cranial fossa. It is defined as a high-grade ependymoma situated in the posterior fossa.
Supratentorial ependymoma is a type of high-grade ependymoma defined as a high-grade ependymoma located within the supratentorial region of the brain.
YAP1-MAMLD1 fusion positive supratentorial ependymoma is a type of supratentorial ependymoma. It is defined as a supratentorial ependymoma that has its material basis in YAP1-MAMLD1 fusion.

Rela fusion positive ependymoma is a type of supratentorial ependymoma, defined as a supratentorial ependymoma that has its material basis in the presence of a RELA fusion gene. It is also exactly synonymous with C11orf95 fusion-positive supratentorial ependymoma and Supratentorial C11ORF95-RELA fused ependymoma.

Bainbridge Ropers Syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by delayed psychomotor development, severe intellectual disability with poor or absent speech, hypotonia, feeding difficulties, poor growth, and dysmorphic facial features. This syndrome has a material basis in both autosomal dominant inheritance and loss of function variant, specifically in heterozygous mutation in the ASXL3 gene on chromosome 18q12. Furthermore, Bainbridge Ropers Syndrome is exactly synonymous with ASXL3-related disorder.
Lipofibromatosis-like neural tumor is a type of connective tissue cancer, defined as a connective tissue cancer that has its material basis in LMNA-NTRK1 gene fusion.

Rapidly involuting congenital hemangioma is a type of physical disorder, hemangioma, and something that at least has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a hemangioma that is characterized by complete regression.

Pericytoma with t(7;12) is a type of perivascular tumor and also falls into the category of entities that at least have a material basis in some translocation and some gene fusion. It is defined as a perivascular tumor characterized by a perivascular pattern of spindle-to-ovoid cell proliferation, having a material basis in t(7;12)(p22;q13) translocation with resultant ACTB-GLI1 fusion.

Solitary fibrous tumor hemangiopericytoma is a type of connective tissue cancer and is defined as a connective tissue cancer characterized as the combination of solitary fibrous tumors and hemangiopericytomas.

Cerebellofaciodental syndrome, also known exactly as cerebellar-facial-dental syndrome, is a syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases, meaning it at least has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This syndrome is characterized by delayed development, intellectual disability, abnormal facial and dental findings, and cerebellar hypoplasia. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the BRF1 gene located on chromosome 14q32.

Lung pleomorphic carcinoma is a type of lung cancer, pleomorphic carcinoma, and something that is at the intersection of cancer and a disease located in the lung. It is defined as a pleomorphic carcinoma characterized by the presence of malignant glandular or squamous cells, along with malignant giant and spindle cells, and is located in the lung.

Oral rhabdomyosarcoma is a type of rhabdomyosarcoma and a type of oral cavity cancer. It represents an intersection of cancers and diseases located in the oral cavity. Additionally, oral rhabdomyosarcoma is defined as a rhabdomyosarcoma located in the oral cavity.

Bladder sarcomatoid transitional cell carcinoma is a type of urinary bladder cancer and a subtype of sarcomatoid transitional cell carcinoma. It is defined as a sarcomatoid transitional cell carcinoma that is located in the bladder. Furthermore, it represents an intersection of cancers and diseases that originate from epithelial cells and are located in the urinary bladder.
Bladder small cell carcinoma is a type of bladder carcinoma, characterized as an undifferentiated neoplasm composed of primitive-appearing cells.

Embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes C19MC altered is a type of embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes, which is defined as an embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes that is characterized by the formation of multilayered rosettes and the amplification of the C19MC region on chromosome 19 (19q13.42). It is also exactly synonymous with ependymoblastoma.

Astroblastoma MN1 altered is a type of astroblastoma that is defined as an astroblastoma characterized by astroblastoma-like morphology with MN1 rearrangements involving the meningioma 1 (MN1) gene on chromosome 22q. It also has the exact synonym CNS high-grade neuroepithelial tumors with MN1 alteration.

Central nervous system neuroblastoma is a type of central nervous system germ cell tumor. It is defined as a central nervous system germ cell tumor characterized by the presence of neuroblastic cells, the absence of ganglion cells, and the absence of a prominent Schwannian stroma formation, arising from the cerebral hemispheres.

CNS neuroblastoma with FOXR2 activation is a type of central nervous system neuroblastoma characterized by FOXR2 activation and composed of small, round cells with hyperchromatic nuclei surrounded by a clear halo. This condition has exact synonyms, including CNS NB-FOXR2, CNS neuroblastoma, FOXR2-activated, and central nervous system neuroblastoma with FOXR2 activation.

Cockayne Syndrome A is a type of Cockayne Syndrome, which is defined by a Cockayne syndrome that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding the group 8 excision repair cross-complementing protein on chromosome 5q11. Furthermore, Cockayne Syndrome A is exactly synonymous with both Cockayne Syndrome Type 1 and Cockayne Syndrome Type I.

Cockayne Syndrome B is a type of Cockayne Syndrome that is defined by severe physical and mental retardation, microcephaly, progressive neurologic and retinal degeneration, skeletal abnormalities, gait defects, and sun sensitivity, without an increased frequency of cancer. It has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding the group 6 excision repair cross-complementing protein on chromosome 10q11. Furthermore, Cockayne Syndrome B is exactly synonymous with Cockayne Syndrome 2 and Cockayne Syndrome Type II.

Castration-resistant prostate carcinoma is a type of prostate carcinoma characterized by continued growth and spread despite the surgical removal of the testes or medical intervention to block androgen production. Furthermore, it has a broader match with MESH:D064129.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome is a type of Cockayne syndrome and it is defined as a Cockayne syndrome characterized by very severe prenatal developmental anomalies, including microcephaly, congenital cataracts, severe mental retardation, facial dysmorphism, and arthrogryposis.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 1 is a type of cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome, defined by a cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC6 gene on chromosome 10q11.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 2 is a type of cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome with a definition that encompasses being a cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome that has its material basis in compound heterozygous mutation in the DNA repair gene XPD (ERCC2) located on chromosome 19q13.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 3 is a type of cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome, defined by a cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous mutation in the ERCC5 gene on chromosome 13q33.

Cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome 4 is a type of cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome, which is defined as a cerebrooculofacioskeletal syndrome that has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ERCC1 gene on chromosome 19q13.

Histiocytic sarcoma is a type of histiocytic and dendritic cell cancer, which is defined as a histiocytic and dendritic cell cancer characterized by the presence of neoplastic cells with morphologic and immunophenotypic characteristics similar to those seen in mature histiocytes. Additionally, histiocytic sarcoma has an exact match with the MESH identifier D054747.

Erythroleukemia is a type of acute erythroid leukemia, which is defined as an acute erythroid leukemia characterized by the presence of at least 50% erythroid precursors and at least 20% myeloblasts in the bone marrow.

Sporadic amyotrophic lateral sclerosis is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis characterized by the random occurrence of ALS without any known cause or a familial member with ALS.

Polymicrogyria is a type of brain disease defined as a malformation of the developing brain characterized by abnormal cortical lamination and an unusual folding pattern of the cerebral cortex. This results in all or part of the brain surface being taken up by an excessive number of small folds (gyri).

Unilateral focal polymicrogyria, which is a type of polymicrogyria, is defined as a polymicrogyria characterized by excessive cortical folding and abnormal cortical layering. It affects only one small region of the brain and may show no neurologic involvement.
Bilateral generalized polymicrogyria is a type of polymicrogyria that is characterized by severe intellectual disability, problems with movement, and seizures, and it affects the entire brain.

Bilateral frontal polymicrogyria is a type of polymicrogyria and also falls under the category of diseases that feature some intellectual disability. It is defined as a polymicrogyria characterized by a symmetric and bilateral form in both brain hemispheres, exclusively involving the frontal lobes without affecting the area behind the Sylvius fissure or the area behind the Rolando sulcus. The symptoms of this condition include delayed motor and language milestones, spastic hemiparesis (stiffness and weakness in one side of the body) or quadriparesis (weakness in all four limbs), and mild to moderate intellectual disability.

Bilateral frontoparietal polymicrogyria is a type of polymicrogyria that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases. It is also recognized as a condition that, at a minimum, has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific polymicrogyria is defined by its excessive cortical folding and abnormal cortical layering, primarily affecting the frontoparietal region of the brain. It is characterized by symptoms including hypotonia, developmental delay, moderate to severe intellectual disability, pyramidal signs, epileptic seizures, non-progressive cerebellar ataxia, dysconjugate gaze, and/or strabismus. The condition has its material basis in a homozygous mutation in the ADGRG1 gene located on chromosome 16q21.

Bilateral parasagittal parieto occipital polymicrogyria is a type of autosomal recessive disease, polymicrogyria, and is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a polymicrogyria characterized by bilateral malformation of cortical development, centered around the parasagittal and mesial aspects of the parietooccipital cortex, and has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the FIG4 gene on chromosome 6q21. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: bilateral temporooccipital polymicrogyria.

Bilateral perisylvian polymicrogyria is a type of polymicrogyria characterized by strikingly restricted polymicrogyria limited to the cortex surrounding the Sylvian fissure. It has a material basis in a homozygous deletion of one 15-bp tandem repeat in a regulatory region of exon 1m of the ADGRG1 gene on chromosome 16q21.

Cytochrome p450 oxidoreductase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a steroid inherited metabolic disorder, which inherently has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. This disorder is defined as a steroid inherited metabolic disorder characterized by combined deficiency of P450C17 and P450C21, along with the accumulation of steroid metabolites. This condition arises due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POR gene, encoding cytochrome p450 oxidoreductase, located on chromosome 7q11.2.

7q11 23 duplication syndrome is a type of chromosomal duplication syndrome characterized by a range of symptoms including motor, speech and language delay, behavior problems, intellectual disability, low muscle tone (hypotonia), an increased head circumference (macrocephaly), facial dysmorphism, seizures, brain abnormalities, and heart defects such as enlargement of the blood vessel that carries blood from the heart to the rest of the body (aortic dilatation). This condition occurs due to an extra copy of a region on the long arm of chromosome 7. It is also known by exact synonyms such as 7q11.23 microduplication syndrome, William-Beuren region duplication syndrome, and chromosome 7q11.23 duplication syndrome.

Apolipoprotein A IV associated amyloidosis is a type of kidney disease and a specific form of amyloidosis that occurs in the kidneys. It is recognized by a slowly progressive renal dysfunction, increased serum creatinine, mostly normal urine analysis with no significant proteinuria, and associated heart disease. Additionally, it is also known by its exact synonyms: AApoAIV amyloidosis and renal AApoAIV amyloidosis.

Dialysis-related amyloidosis is a type of amyloidosis and a form of kidney disease, indicating it is a disease that affects the kidneys. It is characterized by the deposition of amyloid fibrils, predominantly composed of 2 microglobulins (2M), in the osteoarticular structures and viscera, representing a significant complication of long-term dialysis therapy. Furthermore, dialysis-related amyloidosis is also known by several exact synonyms, including ABeta2M amyloidosis, Amyloidosis Beta2M, A2M amyloidosis, Beta2-microglobulinic amyloidosis, and dialysis-related beta2-microglobulin amyloidosis.

Variant a beta2m amyloidosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and amyloidosis, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as an amyloidosis characterized by the accumulation and extensive visceral deposition of an amyloidogenic variant of beta 2 microglobulin, leading to progressive gastrointestinal dysfunction, Sjgren syndrome, and autonomic neuropathy. Furthermore, it has an exact synonym: Autosomal dominant beta2-microglobulinic amyloidosis.

Primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis 1 is a type of primary cutaneous amyloidosis, defined as a primary cutaneous amyloidosis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding oncostatin M receptor-beta (OSMR) on chromosome 5p13. It is also exactly synonymous with familial primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis-1.

Primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis 2 is a type of primary cutaneous amyloidosis. It is defined as a primary cutaneous amyloidosis that has its material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the IL31RA gene located on chromosome 5q11.

Primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis 3 is a type of primary cutaneous amyloidosis and has the exact synonym Amyloidosis cutis dyschromica. It is defined as a primary cutaneous amyloidosis characterized by deposits of keratinocyte-derived amyloid in the skin. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GPNMB gene on chromosome 7p15. The onset of primary localized cutaneous amyloidosis 3 occurs before puberty and involves macular or reticulate hyperpigmentation admixed with symmetrically distributed guttate hypopigmented and hyperpigmented lesions.

Immunoglobulin light chain amyloidosis is a type of heart disease, liver disease, kidney disease, inherited metabolic disorder, and amyloidosis. It is associated with diseases that have a basis in some structural variant and are located in the heart, nerves, liver, and kidneys. This condition is characterized by misfolded and aggregated amyloidogenic immunoglobulin light chains produced by marrow clonal plasma cells. Immunoglobulin light chain amyloidosis is also known by several exact synonyms, including AL amyloidosis, Amyloidosis primary systemic, Light chain amyloidosis, Primary AL amyloidosis, Primary systemic AL amyloidosis, Primary systemic amyloidosis, and Systemic AL amyloidsis.

Immunoglobulin heavy chain amyloidosis is a type of kidney disease and a type of amyloidosis that is particularly located in the kidneys. This condition is defined as an amyloidosis characterized by the aggregation and deposition of amyloid fibrils composed of monoclonal immunoglobulin heavy-chain fragments, usually produced by a plasma cell neoplasm. It is also known by several exact synonyms including AH amyloidosis, Amyloidosis derived from immunoglobulin heavy chain, Heavy chain amyloidosis, and Ig heavy-chainassociated amyloidosis.

Immunoglobulin heavy and light chain is a type of amyloidosis characterized by both Ig heavy chains and light chains contributing to the amyloid fibrils. It has exact synonyms, including AH/AL amyloidosis and Ig heavy-and-light-chain amyloidosis.

Serum amyloid A amyloidosis is a type of amyloidosis that affects various organs, including the spleen, liver, and kidneys. It is defined as an amyloidosis characterized by sustained high levels of inflammatory serum amyloid A protein when inflammation is present in the body. Additionally, serum amyloid A amyloidosis is known by several exact synonyms: AA amyloidosis, Apo serum amyloid A amyloidosis, inflammation AA amyloidosis, and secondary amyloidosis.

Wild type amyloidosis is a type of heart disease and a specific form of amyloidosis that occurs in the heart. It is characterized by the progressive instability, misfolding, and formation of amyloid fibrils of the transthyretin protein. Wild type amyloidosis is also known by several exact synonyms: ATTRwt amyloidosis, Age-related amyloidosis, Old age amyloidosis, Senile systemic amyloidosis, Wild-type ATTR amyloidosis, and Wild-type transthyretin cardiac amyloidosis.

Nonobstructive coronary artery disease is a type of coronary artery disease characterized by atherosclerotic plaque that would not be expected to obstruct blood flow or result in anginal symptoms, and stenosis of the coronary artery is less than 50 percent. It exhibits symptoms such as pain, shoulder pain, severe chest pain, and neck pain. Additionally, this condition features some degree of coronary stenosis. Nonobstructive coronary artery disease is also precisely known as non-CAD.

Hereditary angioedema type I is a type of hereditary angioedema, classified under autosomal recessive diseases. It has a material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance patterns. Moreover, it is defined as a hereditary angioedema that arises from a heterozygous mutation in the C1 inhibitor gene (C1NH, SERPING1) on chromosome 11q.

Hereditary angioedema type III is a type of hereditary angioedema, characterized clinically by recurrent skin swelling, abdominal pain attacks, and potentially life-threatening upper airway obstruction. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding coagulation factor XII (F12) on chromosome 5q35.
Acquired angioedema is a type of angioedema that is characterized by an acquired deficiency of C1-INH (C1-Inhibitor), caused by either consumption or inactivation.

Anauxetic dysplasia is a type of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, which is defined as a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia characterized by the prenatal onset of extreme short stature, an adult height of less than 85 cm, hypodontia, and mild mental retardation.

46 XX sex reversal 5 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a specific form of 46 XX sex reversal. It is characterized by a condition that at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. The definition of 46 XX sex reversal 5 includes it being a 46,XX sex reversal that is characterized by genital virilization in 46,XX individuals. This condition is also associated with congenital heart disease and variable somatic anomalies including blepharophimosis-ptosis-epicanthus inversus syndrome and congenital diaphragmatic hernia. Its material basis is in a heterozygous mutation in the NR2F2 gene on chromosome 15q26.

Familial Behcet like autoinflammatory syndrome is classified as a type of autosomal dominant disease, primary immunodeficiency disease, and a condition that fundamentally arises from some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by ulceration of mucosal surfaces, especially in the oral and genital areas, and is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the TNFAIP3 gene on chromosome 6q23. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with A20 haploinsufficiency.

Abdominal obesity metabolic syndrome 4 is a type of abdominal obesity metabolic syndrome, characterized by obesity, hypertension, and early-onset coronary artery disease. This condition is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CELA2A gene located on chromosome 1p36.

Retinal dystrophy with leukodystrophy is a type of disease that falls into the categories of autosomal recessive disease, peroxisomal disease, and those that have a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a peroxisomal disease characterized by a peroxisomal enzyme deficiency caused by impaired very long chain fatty acid (VLCFA) metabolism, which has its material basis in homozygous mutations in the ACBD5 gene located on chromosome 10p12. Additionally, this condition is exactly synonymous with ACBD5 deficiency.
Acute flaccid myelitis is a type of myelitis that is defined by an acute onset of flaccid weakness in one or more limbs.

Agenesis of corpus callosum cardiac ocular and genital syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by global developmental delay and/or intellectual disability, corpus callosum agenesis or hypoplasia, craniofacial dysmorphisms, and ocular, cardiac, and genital anomalies. This syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CDH2 gene on chromosome 18q12.

Alcoholic ketoacidosis is a type of metabolic acidosis and also falls under the category of conditions that are driven by the consumption of alcohol. It is defined as a metabolic acidosis characterized by the accumulation of ketones in the blood, which occurs as a result of the body breaking down fat for energy due to alcohol use. Ketones are a type of acid.

Alopecia mental retardation syndrome 4 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a variant of alopecia mental retardation syndrome. It is categorized under conditions that have a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, this syndrome is defined by an alopecia-mental retardation syndrome that originates from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the LSS gene located on chromosome 21q22.
